commit_message:
Do not try to introspect nodes in maintenance mode and associated ones

Some time ago ironic-discoverd used to require maintenance mode.
This was changed back in Kilo, and was deprecated in Liberty.

Also cleans up introspection code a bit.

Change-Id: Ib2ea84a8e7f0a42423199cd1db40136ab8495fdc

commit_message:
Add new context manager for shade exceptions, cont. again

This commit continues the work of
 change Ic39b6e3efc33b7a30f298a3daca6d6c16ab4ca89

Shade has developed a common pattern within many of the API
methods where we try to avoid re-wrapping OpenStackClientException
exceptions by catching them and simply re-raising. We can eliminate
this duplicate exception handling with a context manager.

Change-Id: Ic714673e842847c987166fe4a7bf43965dd4d8a9

commit_message:
Get noop drivers to function within flows

The noop drivers suffered from not being updated and just not being tested
with being called within flows like normal real op drivers.  This gets the noop
drivers to succeed when called liked other drivers.  They do not do anything
and will return fake information whenever it is required they return data.
This can be improved later so that they actually do their own data store, but
that would require a much larger update and I'm not sure there's much value
in it.

Change-Id: I2627ed35c0f576f8cfa258b542e5bdb4be03dac8
Closes-Bug: #1501190

commit_message:
Add ansible-role-nodepool project

In this patch, we are just adding ansible-role-nodepool into the
OpenStack gerrit workflow. After talking with both openstack-infra and
third party CI teams it was decided to deal with which team this would
be part of at a later date.

Additionally, we have not created a launchpad project for this module
or pypi (since we won't release there).

Gerritbot was also not configured at this time, since we don't know
which team we are going to be part of.

Change-Id: I8e9c4008648d55cd6c08ffc87ea54f24c55f9f61
Signed-off-by: Paul Belanger <pabelanger@redhat.com>

Use assertIsNone instead of assertEqual(None, ***)

Instead of using assertEqual(None, ***), developers should
use assertIsNone(***).

Change-Id: Id0861258ae9dda119db3e7b88990ebbf646e42b8
Related-Bug: #1510006

[{'created': '2015-11-09 21:58:40.000000000', 'message': "skip lock_unlock_server test for cells

The cells architecture of doing db replay makes this call
fundamentally racey for cells. The contract is that if you request an
action on a server and it is locked, you get a 409 at the API, and are
done. If you get a 2xx, the resource is not locked, and life is good.

Except in cells, the API db will be updated, and the API will return
all is well. Except the db replay hasn't happened for the cell, so the
additional check in the nova compute for locked blows up.

The fix probably involves the nova-compute check doing a timed retry
under cells because of replication lags.

Related-Bug: #1466696
"}]
commit_message:
skip lock_unlock_server test for cells

The cells architecture of doing db replay makes this call
fundamentally racey for cells. The contract is that if you request an
action on a server and it is locked, you get a 409 at the API, and are
done. If you get a 2xx, the resource is not locked, and life is good.

Except in cells, the API db will be updated, and the API will return
all is well. Except the db replay hasn't happened for the cell, so the
additional check in the nova compute for locked blows up.

The fix probably involves the nova-compute check doing a timed retry
under cells because of replication lags.

Change-Id: Ic18407b8372c286d8e258860f3e2bf76eceef2aa
Related-Bug: #1466696

Implement cinder type-show

This patch adds the type-show command to the
cinder CLI for viewing information on volume
types.

Closes-Bug: #1505806

Dean, as I'm not a regular openstack client contributor, I'm unclear on the expectations for these types of changes. I would like to be able to use the openstack client to at least perform the same functions as via the nova client. 

None of what you are asking is available via the nova client today so would have to be additional logic placed in the openstack client. I would argue that your request for improvements to provide --host and service-name support could be added at a later date if such a use case presents itself. My use case is not to do it via name as I want to leverage the ID to target specific item. I'm not a nova expert so I don't know if there is a unique requirement on host/service name. I don't think there are as I think there might be additional constraints around zone.

I feel that the request to add the ability to remove via host or a name is beyond this initial review and functionality that could be added at a later date.  Right now the openstack client has no function to remove a service. This is to add at least an equivalent to the 'nova service-delete' call."}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2015-10-08 17:33:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Alex, OSC is more than just an equivalent to the nova command, or just a wrapper around the novaclient python API.  One of the things we do consistently is allow resources to be specified by name whenever possible (the exceptions to this are when the names are not unique or there is no name).

We have a LOT of incomplete commands that will be 'added later', even more so with testing (thank you for including that) and docs (also missing).  Adding the --host option, if it even makes sense to have one, can be done later, but I consider the name lookup to be fundamental to our use model."}, {'account_id': 14985, 'date': '2015-10-08 17:39:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I can look into it but I have concerns that name is not unique in this case. I think name/host/zone might be unique but like I said I'm not a nova guy.  --host only makes sense in terms wider searches.  My concern is that doing things via name in this case can lead to accidental deletions. I would rather that removals and deletions be explicit by default rather than doing some search & purge just because."}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2015-10-08 17:57:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Then I suppose I should be worried about the set command that requires both a name and host.

In any case I am not willingly going to add to our already deep technical debt.'}, {'account_id': 6482, 'date': '2015-10-09 02:21:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)'}, {'account_id': 14985, 'date': '2015-10-09 14:45:41.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 14985, 'date': '2015-10-09 15:16:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Workflow-1

I've updated this, but I disagree with the argument behind this.  Using the name <service> for something that needs to be an ID is not a good user experience. Also using ID is already a pattern within the compute commands...

https://github.com/openstack/python-openstackclient/blob/master/openstackclient/compute/v2/agent.py#L84-L87

I understand the argument for consistency, but I just don't think this is the command to be picking a battle over.  I'm working on the docs now."}, {'account_id': 14985, 'date': '2015-10-09 15:35:02.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-09 17:04:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

commit_message:
Add compute service delete

This change adds 'compute service delete <service>' to the openstack
client. This is the equivalent of 'nova service-delete <id>'

Change-Id: I69ef1cac72cbe125c2114f8e958e22350a70f367
Closes-Bug: #1503510

commit_message:
Remove force build of tripleo-puppet-elements

This was only needed because we didn't include tripleo-puppet-elements
in the package white list for unpinned projects. We now include
tripleo-puppet-elements in this white list so we can remove the workaround.

Change-Id: I508f578164ac4e8bae7adab86181cea1617fcb88

commit_message:
Identity API v3 only jobs non-voting in QA repos

There is an experimental gate job for Identity API
v3 only for DevStack and Tempest repositories,
where the Identity v2 API is disabled.

That job aims to verify that Tempest tests can run
with the described configuration, and consequently
services are compatible with the Identity API v3.

It was made experimental because DevStack was not
using the Identity API v3 to set resources up and
Tempest tests were failing. Now that they are
fixed, the job is passing (see change #213430 as
an example).

This change moves the job from the experimental
pipeline to the main check pipeline for the
DevStack project, making it non-voting for now.

The same change will be done for Tempest after the
Juno EOL date, because there are already too many
tempest jobs running on check.

The goal is, once there is enough confidence on
its stability, to make it voting.

Change-Id: I54f899a9bd2bce94d221933ddaaf35683331766c

commit_message:
Cue genconfig

This updates tox -egenconfig to correctly generate configuration
files for the various components of cue. Included are list_opts
invocations for all places where configuration is found, appropriate
setup.cfg hooks for generic oslo-config-generator invocations, and
explicit genconfig configuration files for the monitor, worker, and api.

Sample configurations have been regenerated from source.

Change-Id: Ib838269b3ba1e81587cd984933edb41d6d6a555a

commit_message:
Fix ordering of project gauges on the home page

The project gauges used to be sorted by failure rate, but a recent
change broke this behavior (_.sortBy and Array.sort work in slightly
different ways).

This refactors the comparison function to comply with Array.sort
instead. It also changes the current test data so that we can test this
behavior as well.

Co-Authored-By: Dhiana Deva <ddeva@thoughtworks.com>
Co-Authored-By: Caio Carrara <ccarrara@thoughtworks.com>
Change-Id: Ifd9c379d805e2e62b3d89b54a6544974a8d6972a

commit_message:
Run gate-project-config-bashate on .sh files only

Like pep8 before we are trying to reduce the amount of jobs launched
in the check / gate pipelines. Over the last 200 commits only 2 or 3
files have been touched.

We are also reducing run-bashate.sh and remove unsourced files.

Change-Id: Ie77fad9a272fb41fbb48f94ceee910954e903939
Signed-off-by: Paul Belanger <pabelanger@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Improve neutron-client error message output

In case a user provides incorrect input, the NOVA CLIs provide
information regarding usage of the NOVA help CLI. This is useful
for new users. Similar information has been updated in the neutron
CLIs as well.

Change-Id: I1be2ba5a2c937b58900221a9ec7625c461ac17d9
Closes-Bug: #1495742

I think I would rather we have output options that made sense for swift and didn't invoke any sort of relationship with `ls` - I particularly don't care for `swift list --lh` (gag).

What would the ideal output look like?"}, {'account_id': 18015, 'date': '2015-11-03 20:08:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

soft -1'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2015-11-09 21:37:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

meh, I liked it better just adding it to -l

I think the --content-type option is annoying

a) do we really think it's reasonable for everyone to have to make an alias to get the output of swift list that they want

b) do we really think it's reasonable for arbitrary brittle parsers to have to deal with swift list -l

I think if we're worried about computers parsing the output we should give them a decent format to parse (I would suggest --json).  I think we humans deserve the content-type [1].

1. I recognize this is a flip-flop on my original trepidation, but then I needed content-type and I used the patch and my life was measurably better.  Why shouldn't we change the client to make everyone's lives better!?  FWIW, --content-type would have also probably made my life marginally improved over the status quo, so I'm +1 on this change as is too.  I just the think justification of supporting parsing of swift list -l format is mistake and we shouldn't take it as a reasonable goal moving forward (this is unrelated to exposing content-type in the listings which I'm now sure is a win).  If someone else +2's this change you could probably hit me up for a +A - but I'd rather go back to the previous change set and merge that (hence my +2 on it!)."}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2015-11-09 21:38:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

-c alias for --content-type can be added in follow up, but --ct would be terrible.'}, {'account_id': 16896, 'date': '2015-11-09 21:39:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Peter, I agree with Clay that the first option was a better approach. I'm shooting for simplicity, not sure adding --content-type helps that much and Clay had a good argument that the format is not very prone for parsing anyway.

I agree that if we are are going to provide a new flag, it seems to make more sense to provide --json."}, {'account_id': 6968, 'date': '2015-11-11 10:51:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

I also agree with Clay, I prefer patchset 2 more.

I'm just wondering about the order in the list. Patchset 2 returns the content-type before the name, and if someone parses the output of the CLI this will break - the object names are now in the next column. Even worse, the the content-type column might extend to another tabstop, misaligning that line. Here is an example what I mean:

 vagrant@saio:~/python-swiftclient$ swift list public --long
         2357 2015-10-23 14:37:34                text/html example_03.html
         2321 2015-10-23 14:37:34   application/javascript example_03.js
            6 2015-11-03 10:34:22 application/x-www-form-urlencoded testfile

It might make sense to put the content-type in the last column: if someone parses the output it is very likely that it still works, and the beginning of the object name is always at the same position. However, the content-type column might not be aligned well then, because the object name might be quite long... 

Anyways, I'm fine with patchset 2 either with the content-type at the current position or after the object name. Both have pros and cons, and we can't satisfy everyone at the same time - so let's go for one or the other."}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2015-11-11 11:21:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

if someone is parsing the output how do you know they're not doing it with `swift list -l | awk '{print $NF}'` to get the *last* column.

trying to support parsers of this not-for-computer output is not a game we can win IMHO.

We should stick content-type in --long where ever it looks better."}, {'account_id': 18015, 'date': '2015-11-11 11:22:03.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 18015, 'date': '2015-11-11 11:23:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Bump PyECLib version to >=1.0.7

This is the first step in updating PyECLib to 1.1.1. Once
this change lands, we plan to update Swift requirements to
>=1.0.7 before updating global-requirements and upper-
constraints to 1.1.1.

Context: The new version of PyECLib introduces native EC
backend named 'liberasurecode_rs_vand' that provides an
alternative to the current 'jerasure_rs_vand' default.
Also brings in a number of bug fixes including those for
issues on big-endian archs.

Change-Id: Ib4bbeb7dfd2ba8f00e269f99f984ade72a77eebc

commit_message:
Fix get_class_name() on Python 3

Modify oslo_utils.reflection.get_class_name() to return the same result
on Python 2 and Python 3. Use obj.__name__ instead of obj.__qualname__
on Python 3.

Closes-Bug:1513067

Change-Id: If589ed2b67b42bcce6e920f6f7061eee5732f55b

commit_message:
Convert exceptions to MigrationPreCheckError

Exceptions returned during pre live migration should be
MigrationPreCheckError exceptions otherwise the instance will
be set to error state.

Change-Id: I231c2bacbe06072421073e92a9048bf97b263230
Closes-Bug: #1513643

commit_message:
Port cinder.hacking to Python 3

Fix the N325 check on Python 3: the AST changed between Python 2 and
Python 3 for try/except.

tox.ini: Add cinder.tests.unit.test_hacking to Python 3.4.

Partial-Implements: blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: I7c7d1c5e52f525ade14b13ecf2dec1681997da22

commit_message:
Plugin is able to extend existing network roles

The same network role from different plugins can be merged
according to policy of merge, that allows each plugin to extend the VIP for role.

TestCheckVIPsNames was deleted, because this patch makes it obsolete.

Change-Id: I81e773e53ab67b4e7d424805134c0d86dcc7a43a
Closes-Bug: #1487011

[{'created': '2015-11-11 15:52:14.000000000', 'message': "Rename jobs for Kolla

Due to the length of the job name and the tox target we run into an
uncommon limitation; the virtualenv that tox launches is nested in a
path that is too long. This leads to and error on our longest named
job which prevents tox from running at all.

This limitation is the limit for the line length of the first line
in a shell script. See `man execve` for more info. A quote from that
manpage: 'A maximum line length of 127 characters is allowed for the
first line in a #! executable shell script.'

Change-Id: I43fba2a5ff1890d699045496c9eaee5e849f3e75
Backport: Liberty
Partially-Implements: blueprint multinode-gate
"}]
commit_message:
Rename jobs for Kolla

Due to the length of the job name and the tox target we run into an
uncommon limitation; the virtualenv that tox launches is nested in a
path that is too long. This leads to and error on our longest named
job which prevents tox from running at all.

This limitation is the limit for the line length of the first line
in a shell script. See `man execve` for more info. A quote from that
manpage: 'A maximum line length of 127 characters is allowed for the
first line in a #! executable shell script.'

Change-Id: I43fba2a5ff1890d699045496c9eaee5e849f3e75
Backport: Liberty
Partially-Implements: blueprint multinode-gate

commit_message:
Fix test_connect_volume when skip is bypassed

If you run the unit tests with a live /dev/disk/by-path
on the system, the tests fall through the skipUnless
decorators.  This exposed some failures in the expected
commands, which were incorrect.   The expected commands
in _test_connect_volume had assumed the multipath set of
commands which included a rescan.

This patch removes the rescan expected tests, as those
are only run for multipath related attaches.

Closes-Bug: #1514611
Change-Id: If2e77af2a63c33df2f190f77b6ba4cea0bc31b31

commit_message:
Changed bootstrap repositories management

 * Add ability to add extra repositories in new display format
 * Change repositories storing format
 * Add ability to create 'list' and 'button' widgets
 * Minor refactoring

Change-Id: Iddb868050791711c80d8fae7bd7f0426132a1a7d
Partially-implements: blueprint dynamically-build-bootstrap-fuel-menu

commit_message:
Nova module update for Liberty

New merge commit from master branch was done
for nova module, and also some additional patches
were added to fix nova providers:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/229895/
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/226862/
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/229548/

Fix .fixtures.yml for OpenStack module
(according to Puppetfile changes)

Fix network creation for nova network deployment
(Nova network is going to be removed, so
this part will be removed later as well)

Fix noop test according nova module update

Partial implements: blueprint fuel-puppet-librarian

Change-Id: I5cd3fa0eab862d066d6e9d9765df8d59b783ab6a

commit_message:
ObjectControllers return application errors as 499 on bad read

In the _transfer_data method, we translate all (Exception, Timeout)
into a 499 whereas we should consider translating them to 500 on
particular returning error scenarios.

This affects both ReplicatedObjectController and ECObjectControllear.

Change-Id: I571bbc5b1451243907b094a5718c8735fd824268
Closes-Bug: 1504299

commit_message:
Move bashate to its own gate

This is a trivial change to keep things inline with system-config.
Additionally, this will allow a follow up patch to update pep8 to only
run when .py files changes.

Change-Id: I7981c118b2483147a145617a14a583fe80a20df7
Signed-off-by: Paul Belanger <pabelanger@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Aggregate id is a integer, not a uuid

Id in Aggregate is defined as
id = Column(Integer, primary_key=True, autoincrement=True)
and it's input from API layer, so it's not a uuid format,
it's a integer.

Partial-Bug: #1515222

Change-Id: I75e9aee7a720b69bf5157f6dc1fab9dc655ac54a

commit_message:
Change nova-api-create-aggregate return code

conceptually the create-aggregate should return 201,
however current code returns 200 so in order to make
them consistent, make this change and later by using
microversion, the value can be switch back to 201.

Partial-Bug: #1515222

Change-Id: I02c3c57174e19e4ef604a2b840d76652840cdc13

commit_message:
Don't install git-hg

git-hg is obsoleted by git-remote-hg and no longer present on F22. We
don't use it as the repositories we use are git so instead of trying
to deal with two package names (centos and F22) just stop installing it.

Change-Id: I7835ec90d8bcbf1183b4217b9bc6d7714833d243

commit_message:
Prepare Table Model API for the new distributed architecture

Table Model API uses a python referece to both policy engine class
and datasource_manager class to call its methods. In the new architecture,
API model needs to use RPC calling methods in policy engine and
dataosurce_manager.

This patch changes Table Model API to use rpc style method calling.

Patially-Implements: blueprint dist-api-rpcify-table

Change-Id: I66bbda3b6a5a6f7b76c0c95bf3cb1ed9e3cc6640

- gate-training-labs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/96/239796/1/check/gate-training-labs-python27/de3f593/ : SUCCESS in 1m 06s'}, {'account_id': 11109, 'date': '2015-10-29 00:23:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Workflow-1

I want to add a regression test to check that the dashboard is working correctly. Maybe also add test code to look for signs of errors (as opposed to mere error messages) in the log files. Would also be instructive for trainees. It's probably going to be a second test script besides launch_instance, because it is not part of launching an instance."}, {'account_id': 11109, 'date': '2015-11-02 23:50:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I did quite a bit of testing. Most of the time, it works fine. But if (after building the cluster) you don't wait long enough or wait too long to log in, there may be errors. After logging in successfully, you may see pop up errors saying, for instance "Unable to retrieve usage information" and "Unable to retrieve limit information". I am not convinced that simply raising the error limit is a good solution.'}, {'account_id': 11109, 'date': '2015-11-03 11:22:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Seems to be yet another race, with a twist: I often get errors several times in a row, then successes several times in a row. I have been experimenting with the same cluster since yesterday (complete cluster build, then "PROVIDER=virtualbox ./tools/restore-cluster.sh -c -s" for automatic start or without "-s" and manual VM start). I haven't been able to reproduce the problem accessing the dashboard for a while now. I would to like to know a) what triggers it and/or b) what error messages to look for in the log files.'}, {'account_id': 11109, 'date': '2015-11-03 11:30:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I even launched an instance using the dashboard and logged in using the web console. It worked without a problem (with the standard RAM allocation for the 3 nodes: 1024/1024/512).'}, {'account_id': 7007, 'date': '2015-11-11 16:14:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Ok, sounds good enough to me. I guess I will abandon this patch.'}, {'account_id': 7007, 'date': '2015-11-11 16:15:07.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Works well with default configuration. Unless more people report this issue, there is no need to change the configuration.'}]

commit_message:
Update RAM for controller node

Giving 1.5 GB ram to controller node should eliminate out of
memory issues. Hitting this issue with mysql. Mysql daemon stops
running since it does not get enough RAM.

Change-Id: Icc5ad8e0c5caf8f82960c92dcefd4f78af8d19bd

commit_message:
Remove gate-system-config-nodepool

Remove gate-system-config-nodepool and make gate-project-config-nodepool voting.
This completes the migration of nodepool.yaml from system-config to project-config.

Change-Id: Ibe4627bff813878d7a06756e325e283400b67290
Depends-On: I2b45a7145805368b1598d3a3e8a94f0e4eb8cf2d

commit_message:
Mellanox ethernet driver (mlx4_en) autoloading together with core driver

Mellanox ethernet driver (mlx4_en) should be loaded together together with
core driver (mlx4_core).

Fix for CentOS provisioning, cobbler part.

Change-Id: Ic1c26ff610fc657d05a854e81cf3681f3eeb0c45

commit_message:
Update oslo.middleware to 2.9.0

http_proxy_to_wsgi.py was added in 2.9.0 which designate needs to accept
HTTP_X_FORWARDED_PROTO reliably.

Change-Id: Ib891646158f5993f7ee8997a3b3c535638b3061c

commit_message:
fail if devstack attempts to be run under virtualenv

This has come up on the mailing list recently, we should just fail
early and explicitly so that people don't get way down this path and
not realize it's never going to work.

Change-Id: I8a7f001adf3a5244b8655858ebd5fc7014a4af55

Adding Security Checklist

Adding separate section on Horizon checklists.

and set certain configuration keys for secured communication.

commit_message:
os-vif: introduce definition of os-vif project

os-vif is a project to define an object model and plugin system
to integrate OpenStack network providers (eg Neutron) and
OpenStack compute providers (eg Nova)

Change-Id: Ifc2c1a3198075aafc3fd97f0c5355eb27ba8bc19

commit_message:
Rename list_users_for_tenant to list_tenant_users

This patch renames list_users_for_tenant to list_tenant_users for
fitting the other service clients' methods.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

commit_message:
Publish releasenotes

Enhance releasenote handling and add a post job that publishes the
release notes.

Note that the post jobs will be run on all branches but we need
to publish the content from master since we generate all content
on the master branch.

Add job to post queue for publishing release-notes.

Change-Id: I204e669d532d59bbf6aec0d8d4da4ab183deaf59

commit_message:
Run releasenotes jobs only on liberty and newer

Do not run releasenotes jobs on juno and kilo,
just on liberty, master and future stable branches.

Make it non-voting for now until reno works fine - and thus
remove the job from the gate. This gives projects
also the change to get all infrastructure in place.

Change-Id: Icf6d68ed76a23a680af169fb758fbfd3af6dc168

commit_message:
Revert "Manage keystone initialization directly in t-h-t manifests"

This reverts commit 86d6c1ddc76bad423194e789ffb5474e4e12960e.

This likely has an impact on upgrades, and since we don't
have an upgrade CI job yet I'm concerned that we may have
just broken ourselves.  I would prefer to wait to merge this
until the CI job is in place.

Change-Id: Ib2366cb4b40471a28122f6e9955da9bdb31a53fb

commit_message:
Allow customization of Ceph client user

Previously we enforced the Ceph user used by the OpenStack clients
to be named 'openstack', this change allows for customization
of such a name.

Change-Id: Idef3e1ed4e8e21b645081869b8d6fad2329bdc60

commit_message:
Fix TypeError set param from 'null' to some value

TypeError Exception during attemt to set some resource's parameter from
`null` to some value or value to `null`.

Change-Id: Ib20218f6a8676669230f440a4a13dea61f2d4c6b
Closes-bug: #1514364

commit_message:
Add keystone v3 support to client

All clients should support keystone v3 till kilo. This patch adds
support for keystone sessions, keystone endpoint discovery and support
for the CLI to provide keystone v3 options. Also, bumped glance client
API version to 2 for the compatibility with v3 keystone API.

Change-Id: I565927db7f393c0bae41ebf9c03488f9cd966e79
Co-Authored-By: David Hu <david.hu@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Steve McLellan <steven.j.mclellan@gmail.com>
Closes-Bug: #1354129
Closes-Bug: #1507932
Implements: blueprint support-keystone-v3

[{'created': '2015-09-01 09:23:58.000000000', 'message': 'No hostname validation in launch instance angularjs panel

Horizon Juno does not have hostname validation in AngularJS launch instance
form. For example, you can create a new instance with name: "#3rtttt"

That name will cause problems when Nova try to handle, but Horizon allow
launch a new instance with a not valid hostname. A valid hostname is
specified by RFC1123 (http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc1123).

This patch is quite similar to
https://bugs.launchpad.net/horizon/+bug/1458800 but the validation
happens in different layers. This patch is needed as Horizon supports
the new AngularJS launch instance form.

Change-Id: Id404510b1442e697da1c43df9352146e3126ee6a
Closes-Bug: #1490850
'}]
commit_message:
No hostname validation in launch instance angularjs panel

Horizon Juno does not have hostname validation in AngularJS launch instance
form. For example, you can create a new instance with name: "#3rtttt"

That name will cause problems when Nova try to handle, but Horizon allow
launch a new instance with a not valid hostname. A valid hostname is
specified by RFC1123 (http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc1123).

This patch is quite similar to
https://bugs.launchpad.net/horizon/+bug/1458800 but the validation
happens in different layers. This patch is needed as Horizon supports
the new AngularJS launch instance form.

Change-Id: Id404510b1442e697da1c43df9352146e3126ee6a
Closes-Bug: #1490850

commit_message:
virtozzo storage volume driver in libvirt

The purpose of this spec is to add support for volumes,
hosted by Virtuozzo storage.

Virtuozzo Storage is a fault-tolerant distributed storage system,
optimized for virtualization workloads. From client's point of
view it looks like network attached storage (NFS or GlusterFS).

The CI system will be running on Nova tree and checking each
Nova patch with Virtozzo Storage. The CI aims to eventually
vote on every relevant Nova patchset.

blueprint libvirt-vzstorage-volume-support

Change-Id: I97f68a2d8e261d2c7db98e6916bc52a8068fe5fe

Read through the puppet code for command execution and another option is to just not "combine" stdout and stderr, somewhat stupidly this actually means throw away stderr by sending it to /dev/null. it by generag ruby JSON parser.

commit_message:
Use json output instead plain-text

Openstack CLI utilities can return warning messages while
run to stderr. It's a normal behavior for Openstack CLI.
But Puppet mixs stderr and stdout for commands.

For preventing parsing warning messages,
I propose got response from Neutron CLI as JSON if it required
and parse it by ruby JSON parser.

JSON is a more usable format for interprocess communication,
than plain-text or CSV.

Change-Id: Iba1105bc119272715fa211ac129a366fe50cbf47
Closes-bug: #1508511

commit_message:
Skip TestNetworkAdvancedServerOps if ssh_connect_method != 'floating'

The setup in TestNetworkAdvancedServerOps unconditionally uses floating
IPs to verify the connection to the server instance, which will fail if
CONF.compute.ssh_connect_method != 'floating', so we need to add that
skip check.

Note that the help text for CONF.network.tenant_networks_reachable says:

"Whether tenant networks can be reached directly from the test client.
This must be set to True when the 'fixed' ssh_connect_method is
selected."

However, if you set tenant_networks_reachable=True and have
ssh_connect_method=fixed, the test would still not be skipped and fail.

Closes-Bug: #1513983

Change-Id: Iaae2fe0f98459074a2adfaa00608882e840d98a7

commit_message:
Skip TestSecurityGroupsBasicOps if ssh_connect_method != 'floating'

The setup code in this test requires floating IPs so skip the test
class if CONF.compute.ssh_connect_method != 'floating'.

Change-Id: Ie8dd91610a2e28445873b16f09a258af0eca0652
Closes-Bug: #1513983

commit_message:
Updated Docker and k8s DIB elements

* Kubernetes element was updated to base on v1.0.6
* Docker now has its own repo and has different package name.
  Also it is now installed via downloadable script.
  TODO: Need somehow to fix docker version to 1.8.2

Updated Docker and k8s DIB elements

* Kubernetes element was updated to base on v1.0.6
* Docker now has its own repo and has different package name.
  Also it is now installed via downloadable script.
  TODO: Need somehow to fix docker version to 1.8.2

Implements: blueprint update-k8-to-v1-dib-elements

[verify] Add new script to launch verification job

There several advantages of porting script for verification job on python:
 - easy way for management input options
 - easy way of implementing different modes of job

The cost of {} vs dict() is INCREDIBLY small compared to the full cost when a port is created, or any other Neutron API call.

Let's take port create ... first there may be an API call to keystone to authenticate and get the service catalog, which could hit a database multiple times or the combination of a database and LDAP server, or many other possibilities.  Then we have the Neutron API call, which has multiple db hits and then whatever backend specific work is needed, which could include some messages over AMQP and some stuff in a remote agent.  Unless dict() vs {} is running *many* thousands or millions of times for each *1* request, I seriously doubt you'd be able to demonstrate a difference with this change using profiling data.  Feel free to prove me wrong.  :-)

Performance work is great, really, but I'd rather it be based on data that shows that you're optimizing something that makes a substantial impact.  Otherwise, we don't know if we're wasting time micro optimizing something that doesn't make a difference (dev time, review time, ...)."}, {'account_id': 14323, 'date': '2015-11-11 13:17:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
use {} instead of dict()

The performance of {} is far better than dict(). Please see:
https://doughellmann.com/blog/2012/11/12/the-performance-impact-of-using-dict-instead-of-in-cpython-2-7-2/

A follow up patch will update the unit tests.

Change-Id: I1cc8d4309a70a88918f22e71ba83ca630c93e89e

commit_message:
Enable migration autogenerate

These changes allow a developer to generate migrations using the
autogenerate function without the need to pass in a config file that
includes sql connection information.

Change-Id: I6b3942f7747e8f73e52925c24340e20daeb78911

commit_message:
Create tests for set_default_is_domain in LDAP

Add test that validate whether the _set_default_is_domain_project method
in resource LDAP driver accepts only project refs or a list of project
refs. If so, it sets the is_domain project ref attribute to False.

Change-Id: Ifd0c8ef9ea422f167eda0a786a93febefebb4c6b

commit_message:
Require oslo.log >= 1.12.0

Neutron will crash when using syslog and oslo.log<=1.11.0

The related bug has additional information.

Change-Id: Ia99f1e46b1223fd447399a23c25ab998bb907ec9
Related-Bug: #1499620

commit_message:
Add npm envs to tox

This adds two new test environments for npm test and npm lint so that
developers can just call tox and be sure all tests have been run.

Change-Id: I71d8f5d566b9dbab65e893474b6df56c86c73903
Co-Authored-By: Dhiana Deva <ddeva@thoughtworks.com>

commit_message:
Normalize pre-formatted text on README

This removes initial ``$`` from code lines as most of them didn't have
the dollar sign already (plus it makes it annoying to copy/paste
commands) and normalizes indentation to 4 spaces (again, as most of them
were already formated as such).

Change-Id: I7b77a1fd20134fa5d23a448a17629621ae0a6b05

commit_message:
Avoid removing entries for timers that didn't stop

It seems bad to remove timer objects for timers that
didn't actually stop, so instead of removing all the
timers (including the ones that had issues) only
remove the ones that didn't have issues.

commit_message:
Update README development usage notes

Plain installing the python package is cumbersome if you're doing any
development as new changes will not be picked up. This updates it to
also mention installing the package in development mode.

Change-Id: I48a402c0c4a98401144cb9cf445aff0a9105d169

commit_message:
Fix TypeError exception in test_server_actions setup

test_server_actions use rebuild_server from base class which returns
server's id. But this tests try to fetch 'server' from return value
which results to TypeError.

Change-Id: I5bbfbe6ee4e8acc84112d134d331380a69b637d0
Closes-Bug: #1514685

As mentioned on IRC, this is the wrong approach:

You need to edit the flagmappings file and regenerated this file.

Also, first propose for master, then backport to stable.

So, I suggest to start with a new change for stable and abandon this one.'}, {'account_id': 15519, 'date': '2015-08-27 12:01:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thanks Andreas.
Just a few questions..
1) Should I just edit this file (https://github.com/openstack/openstack-manuals/blob/master/tools/autogenerate-config-flagmappings/keystone.flagmappings) and (doc/common/tables/keystone-auth.xml) ? 
I looked this patch to understand -> https://review.openstack.org/#/c/177168/'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2015-08-27 12:08:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Yes, exactly - and then you need to run the tool to regenerate the content.

But I wonder why saml2 does not show up *at all*, might be some library missing, or an error in how saml2 is setup.'}, {'account_id': 7923, 'date': '2015-08-27 12:53:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I grep'ed in keystone code and couldn't find the definition of a 'saml2' option. There's probably some dynamic parsing that makes this option available at runtime, but it might be tricky to emulate this behavior with our tools.

The change for this patch looks fine but it will be lost the next time we run autohelp (even with a modification in the flagmapping file). The best solution would be to define this option in keystone IMHO."}, {'account_id': 15519, 'date': '2015-08-27 12:59:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi Guavain,
The saml2 option for auth is when you are using federation. (http://docs.openstack.org/developer/keystone/extensions/federation.html)
Can you point what file should i change? Thanks'}, {'account_id': 7923, 'date': '2015-09-07 07:48:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

The thing is that saml2 is not defined as a static option at all in keystone code. It is probably handled dynamically and our scripts can't handle that.

Manually modifying the generated tables is not an option because the next run of the script will override the change. A solution would be to manually create a new table and include it in the doc."}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-10-31 05:52:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hello,

Has there been any recent update to this issue?'}, {'account_id': 10607, 'date': '2015-11-06 00:31:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review'}, {'account_id': 10607, 'date': '2015-11-11 01:19:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Iury has not updated this patch since August 26 and it is just sitting here without further discussion.

Is someone able to take over this patch and fix it up? Or can someone abandon this for later discussion?

Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 7923, 'date': '2015-11-11 05:39:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Add saml plugin information to auth section

The actual documentation don't show that saml2
can be used a method for authentication.

Change-Id: I89fb8b3e06dbb267e37b996252906b66503f7f1e
Closes-Bug: 1488244

[{'created': '2015-11-10 14:46:34.000000000', 'message': 'Remove "Kept for backward-compatibility" comment

There is not plan to deprecate, or even remove, the following specialized classes:

* StrOpt
* IntOpt
* FloatOpt
* ListOpt
* DictOpt
* MultiStrOpt

So remove the comment "Kept for backward-compatibility with options
not using Opt directly" to avoid any confusion.

These classes are widely used in OpenStack, whereas the cfg.Opt class
is not used directly.

Change-Id: I887dea6bcd1a6c17a3a40061a5c3c78104ed0046
'}]
commit_message:
Remove "Kept for backward-compatibility" comment

There is not plan to deprecate, or even remove, the following specialized classes:

* StrOpt
* IntOpt
* FloatOpt
* ListOpt
* DictOpt
* MultiStrOpt

So remove the comment "Kept for backward-compatibility with options
not using Opt directly" to avoid any confusion.

These classes are widely used in OpenStack, whereas the cfg.Opt class
is not used directly.

commit_message:
Change postgres DB encoding

The default encoding (SQL_ASCII) cannot handle long non-ASCII strings properly
 and results in errors when a user defines a node with a long name containing cyrillic characters. 
Long non-ASCII strings are properly supported with UTF-8 encoding.

Change-Id: I6ceebb0b6c57ffb005983df7093f7f82467d486b
Closes-Bug: #1472275

I sudgest to merge this patchset-2 (less risky) and then start investigating on the impact of applying patchset-1 on other distros for a global fix of start_service function.

commit_message:
On Ubuntu: don't start Zookeeper twice

On Ubuntu, if the Zookeeper service is already running, attempting
to start it again fails with non-zero exit code. This patch detects
whether ZK is already started before trying to start it.

Change-Id: If1257152de01fe5fe0351fdbb538bce083edbec0
Closes-Bug: #1513741

commit_message:
Do not rename the nested port resource name for the VIPs

Using vip.yaml instead of $network.yaml implementation for the VIPs
changed the port resource name, causing Heat to delete/create the
resource instead of updating in-place.

Change-Id: I1bc210afd0b0976abc9c67c7b540724c8efb2b31

commit_message:
Add notification of shared resource usage.

We need a system that can properly account for resource capacity and
usage amounts, including when the deployment uses shared resource pools
like shared storage for ephemeral instance disks.

Change-Id: Iddf44ef0c1ef9763a1c3e70af1137e7dab86854c

commit_message:
Disallow query deleted flavor in nova flavor-show

This might need a microversion bump, so submit for discussion.

When a flavor is deleted, it should not be queried by command
nova flavor-show xxx. But currently nova will return the info
even if it's deleted. An alternative is to add some option such
as --force to force query it by admin.

Closes-Bug: 1485767

Change-Id: Ibf8e0bb19a369dbdb7f665473e19bd867609522d

commit_message:
Added method get_legacy_facade() to the _TransactionContextManager

This public method was added to be able to create several
legacy facades from several transaction context managers.

It could be used in Nova where we have two DBs.
There we need some legal way to create two legacy facades
because right now in Nova we create facades by using
private field _factory. It is not quite right.

Change-Id: I96b3dbcbc5a05ac025c247ae6d8abfc988d0295e

commit_message:
Change steps description for create user test

Next steps performs only if SSL is disabled:
* Send authentication request to Horizon
* Confirm that response status is 200.

So add mention about this in test steps

Change-Id: Id458638ecc1e956803a4a37936e4bd07cf56b6dd
Closes-Bug: #1512658

commit_message:
Add job to test ansible modules against shade

Shade needs a job to test the new Ansible 2.0 OpenStack
modules against the latest shade so we can catch breakages.

Change-Id: I0b8d2ccc0344d2213834380d17fdbf665395c5f1

commit_message:
Update method retrieving mounted disks to work with DVD drives

This patch updates the query used by the vmutils
_get_mounted_disk_resource_from_path method so that it can also
retrieve disks attached as DVD drives.

This change is needed by the Nova rescue blueprint implementation.

Change-Id: I3e1ea18128b882c832309875db6de1d112efd67f

commit_message:
Mocking of werkzeug request in test causes errors

Mocking of werkzeug request args raises error on exiting from
'with' block and was removed from analytics tests.

Issues in tests caused by unbound to session SQLAlchemy objects
inside test request were fixed.

Extracting of dict params from HTTP GET request fixed.

Change-Id: I7215247909a8fcd2e4c74b915670ff373538b186
Closes-Bug: #1514337

commit_message:
Add documentation for service catalog format

Tempest does not serve all kind of fancy service cataog format.
Service catalog should be in some standard and consistant format.

This patch adds those in doc to clarify the expected format of catalogs.

Change-Id: I5fb94510c019cca2e81112fb8cf123a3dfab8daf

commit_message:
Fix checks for X-Trans-Id in DLO-related storage tests.

This commit unifies the way how X-Trans-Id header of Swift
API is checked in DLO-related tests with those which use
custom matcher.

Change-Id: Ib8468cdc06ff6b594811c3e2ae131dd9bbdb1ab0
Closes-Bug: #1490942

When removing the gateway of an HA router, the L3 agent tries to
gracefully remove the IP addresses of the gateway interface before
removing it. This fails for non-master nodes since they only contain
the interfaces without holding their actual IP addresses. This change
removes this behaviour completely by directly removing the interface
itself.

commit_message:
Don't remove ip addresses if not master

When setting --admin-state-up=False on an HA router with a gateway set,
standby nodes don't have any ip addresses set on the devices (although
the devices themselves are present). In such cases, Neutron should not
try to un-set those ip addresses before deleting the device itself.

Closes-bug: #1505203
Change-Id: I5df04b2ed1dc08286f6c467111c61c7f97643d66

commit_message:
Don't update .erlang.cookie on every run

Update happens even during no-op commands like 'meta-data' or 'usage'.
During this update there is a short window for a race condition: a shell
redirection truncates the cookie file, and echo writes data there only
after a brief period of time. So erlang may read data from this empty
file and die with error "Too short cookie string".

Change-Id: I4c3201617669f3872145048b77337632cb93558c
Closes-Bug: #1512754

commit_message:
[packetary] Repository class

class Repository composes from:
* RepositryDriver - low-level support for physical repository. deb, yum, etc.
* RepositoryController - infrastcuture method to communicate with driver
* RepositoryApi - high-level class, that provides methods to work with repository

Change-Id: Iaf868fca982d91089e369d13a6fb381ff879ea73
Implements: blueprint refactor-local-mirror-scripts
Partial-Bug: #1487077

commit_message:
Iterate over copy of session.adapters keys in Python2/3

Iterate over a copy of session.adapters keys in both Python 2.x and
Python 3.x.  In Python 3.x, keys() is not a copy, and therefore
items can't be popped from it while iterating.

Note that this patch addresses the following error message which
is new in Python 3.5.  That is, you need to be using Python 3.5+
to reproduce this error.

    RuntimeError: OrderedDict mutated during iteration
    https://bugs.python.org/issue24369
    https://hg.python.org/cpython/rev/0d8679858272

Change-Id: Iaa2be0dc8ef26e51ce5e8f50049c9e8f84418ec0
Closes-Bug: #1483872

the templates have a default for the VLAN range so it's not really required to pass it?"}, {'account_id': 12398, 'date': '2015-11-10 17:50:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

The defaults are actually pretty bad for VLAN ranges. By default, we set the VLAN range to 1:1000. Of course, we also use the VLANs 10,20,30,etc. by default.

My preference would be to require the VLAN ranges when --neutron-network-type is vlan. commit_message:
Require tunnel ranges if network type is VLAN

If the neutron network type is set to 'vlan', then the Neutron tunnel
ranges argument must also be passed.

Change-Id: I82a37db15c034da56c0c2c90146f01aa522226e1

commit_message:
Refactor parsing metadata to a common function

Currently the metadata is parsed using
dict(v.split('=', 1) for v in metadata)
and was used in several places, it could
be better if we refactor it to a common
function. It will make it more readable
and easier to use in the future.

Change-Id: Ib0fcaacdbef65cdcb85ecc0c304f4933bef2627c
Closes-Bug: #1503939

commit_message:
Move Murano RabbitMQ configuration into separate task

 - create separate task for RabbitMQ configuration
 - move RabbitMQ configuration into rabbitmq.pp
 - remove RabbitMQ configuration templates

DocImpact
Implements: blueprint separate-task-for-murano-rabbitmq-configuration
Change-Id: I4233f76a51ca2b3038bb8265972c2edd3e0f1deb

commit_message:
Allow a user to specify a comma separated list of ntp servers

This commits aims to allow a user to specify several ntp servers and not
just one.

Example:

openstack overcloud deploy --templates --ntp-server
0.centos.pool.org,1.centos.pool.org

Change-Id: I4925ef1cf1e565d789981e609c88a07b6e9b28de

commit_message:
OVS agent reacts to events instead of polling

OVSDB monitor generates the events that the OVS agent
needs to process (device added or updated). Instead of
polling the agent processes the queue of events.

Change-Id: I168a3cc3aa96a809153a30635ad7bda29e8ee47c
Partially-Implements: blueprint restructure-l2-agent

commit_message:
layout: Fix regexp for puppet-openstack integration jobs

The change introduced in 295320dc78b20e44c23209766c17bf0677de46d0
update the regexp of puppet-openstack integration job, but matches
a non-existing job (scenario00(1|2)--dsvm). The problem behind that
is now all puppet-openstack integration jobs are voting... and we don't
want that for the moment.

Change-Id: Iceaafefc6202f8182526e8b4461a556cc06d918a

commit_message:
libvirt: runtime image type detection

Let nova compute select resulting image type in runtime
rather than during initialization. In this case, libvirt driver
starts to be able to run instances with different types of images
on the same compute node with adds flexibility.

Change-Id: I5d7d816740b09a253c2dc4e25f6261b2a52a6d35
Implements: blueprint runtime-image-type

Remove deprecated `apiclient'

This has been deprecated for a while and there are better alternative
(keystoneauth1 and cliff) to deal with that.

Change-Id: I2020d73fa9cedb3b3b87c1d8dbc8d437857ec7c2

commit_message:
Add agent_iboot entrypoint

This patch adds a new driver combination/entrypoint so that
the Iboot power driver can be used with an IPA agent
based deployment workflow.

Change-Id: I677e60a333ec65cbd2852270fb091f17428e5e36
Closes-bug: #1514439

Thanks Kan, the code looks good and it works locally. But I just curious should we explore all attributes to user while we only show some of them.
First you want to see some attributes like:
 Ironic node-port-list node-0 --fields uuid address 
Then you want to sort them by :
 Ironic node-port-list node-0 --fields uuid address --sort-key fake
But you get all sortable attributes like Created At and 'updated_at'. 
Is it too much infos?"}, {'account_id': 14810, 'date': '2015-11-10 05:25:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thanks for your comment, Tan. 
I understand that it might be more intuitive when using a sort key that is also listed in the fields, but I think the sort key does not necessarily have to appear in the output fields.

When listing the arguments of the nodes, ports and chassis, it might be with multiple fields involved, and the sort key can be used to list the output by order without must show it. For example, the user can just list the nodes by 'Created At' time to check some of other properties of node, while the user does not really pay attention to the specific creating time of each node.

Besides, if the user does not specify the 'fields' or 'detail' arguments, some of the attributes can not be used as the sort key, such as 'Created At', 'Updated At' these time related properties, although they are in the same table in ironic database.
Also, from the DB side, these attributes in tables all can be used as the index to implement the sorting operation. And realizing these attributes sortable in ironic command will make it consistent.

So, I think making sort keys the same for list command is needed. Hope this explanation can solve your question. Thanks.:)"}, {'account_id': 13362, 'date': '2015-11-11 01:19:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

OK, this make sense to me. Really thanks to your explain, Kan'}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2015-11-11 09:23:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow+1 Code-Review+2

commit_message:
Make sort keys the same for list commands

The sort key used in the list command should be same
no matter with or without detail command.

The commands are:
 For chasis:
    chassis-list
    chassis-node-list
 For node:
    node-list
    node-port-list
 For port:
    port-list

Change-Id: Idc4789618460c627d8ebe0070443585e261a73de
Closes-Bug: #1446450

    def allowed(self, request, image=None):
        if django.VERSION < (1, 5):
            return False
        ...

    class Meta(object):

        row_actions = (..., DownloadImage, DeleteImage,)

        if django.VERSION < (1, 5):
            row_actions = (..., DeleteImage,)

[{'created': '2014-02-19 18:24:55.000000000', 'message': 'Add 'Download Image' option to Images table

Glance API v1 and v2 allow users to download images. python-glanceclient
already supports this by calling the 'image-download' sub-command.

This patch adds a link action to each image table entry allowing users to
download images.

Note that it will only work on django >= 1.5. An "Unable to download image"
message error will be displayed in case django.http.StreamingHttpResponse could
not be imported.

commit_message:
Add 'Download Image' option to Images table

Glance API v1 and v2 allow users to download images. python-glanceclient
already supports this by calling the 'image-download' sub-command.

This patch adds a link action to each image table entry allowing users to
download images.

Note that this feature is only supported on django >= 1.5.

Implements: blueprint download-images-and-snapshots
Change-Id: If2cbd8d88ec5766ba4cf5cbd73f01f7136ece242

commit_message:
stack delete fails when instance is soft deleted

In an environment where reclaim_instance_interval is set to
non-zero in nova, an delete request will only soft delete an
instance.(status=SOFT_DELETED, so that the instance can be reclaimed
if required by using 'nova restore <instance_id>')

Now in the above environment, when an delete stack is requested by
user, stack will hang until reclaim_instance_inerval or timeout.
Hence status=SOFT_DELETED for an instance should be handled by heat, which
this patch proposes.

Closes-Bug: #1377290

Change-Id: I86ea788131f113e3deb7aebfccecd7f5e4957ae5
(cherry picked from commit 633a6bb14413b6a8523b6c142df32a7289e05a93)

commit_message:
Swap manifest location check order in mcollective container

Currently Dockerfile checks if "old" manifest exists, and if not,
proceeds to the to-be-introduced one. This behavior makes it
impossible to make CI pass for I1657ce22be62414abd4a407a5d28292f25915a7b.

The modified conditional will fallback to the old manifest only if new
one doesn't exist.

Related-bug: 1508058
Change-Id: Iab069b6c660edf0c7932a61cc480530447932708

commit_message:
Add call to pluggable IPAM from ml2 delete_subnet

ml2 plugin overrides delete_subnet and do not call super(),
so pluggable IPAM action defined in db_base_plugin_v2 are not called.
As a result subnets can not be deleted from IPAM driver if ml2 plugin
is used.

Added ipam.delete_subnet call into ml2 delete_subnet.
Patch includes UT to verify IPAM driver is called on subnet
allocation and deallocation.
Test class is inherited from TestMl2SubnetsV2, so all SubnetV2 tests are
additionally executed for ml2 plugin with reference IPAM driver.

Closes-Bug: #1510653

Change-Id: I2b7ddfe70a1275a141af38e18151e1fc000e2682

We need to get Nova's LXC support tested.

commit_message:
Remove unnecessary ugettext_lazy

This patch remove unnecessary ugettext_lazy procedure
against database instance name and image name for
page title in its detail view.

Change-Id: I4f9a2b9ca7d43cf6fdf6ae02f50ad2f9c625d602
Closes-Bug: #1515100

commit_message:
Port services to core API

Changes:
- Register services API as core API using old link.
- Remove extension code for services.
- Leave rename of API url for future update which will be done with
  bump of microversion after port of all extensions to core API.

Partially implements bp ext-to-core

Change-Id: I06005e8339f16c404d3f1ff9917480603801d44f

The process of bringing us into compliance with the H405 pep8 rule has left
us with a lot of docstrings that either don't follow the recommendations of
PEP0257, are misleading, wrong, or nonsensical. This patch attempts to fix

commit_message:
Fix garbled docstrings

The process of bringing us into compliance with the H405 pep8 rule has left
us with a lot of docstrings that either don't follow the recommendations of
PEP0257, are misleading, wrong, or nonsensical. This patch attempts to fix
them up.

Change-Id: Icfe90b5ba3102a7e13ab659038a8b2af9019e9e6

all of the necessary changes for its use.

commit_message:
Add new config option for IPv6 Prefix Delegation

With the impending deprecation of the default subnetpool configuration
options, IPv6 PD needs to be enabled with a new config option.

This patch adds the 'ipv6_pd_enabled' option to neutron.conf, and makes
all of the necessary changes for its use.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I43486c5a13ee2ff0097355afe7e1f3ef8794b185
Closes-Bug: 1501835

commit_message:
Apply a naming rule of GET to v2 keystone clients

[GET /resources] methods should be "list_<resource name>s"
or "show_<resource name>", so this patch applies the rule
to v2 keystone clients.
This patch changes some v3 parts also because some tests are
shared between v2 and v3 and the method names should be the same.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: Iea7dcb8839d0dfc300295f3e534d54224f9ec31c

(1 comment)

I'm very much supportive of this approach to the VIF plugin problem. In fact, I'm so supportive of this approach, I created an os_vif library on Friday to get the creative juices flowing:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/193668/1/specs/liberty/os-vif-library.rst

The thing I disagree with (and thus the -1) about this particular proposal are having the os_vif library do libvirt XML configuration -- I think os_vif should be virt-driver agnostic.

All other things I agree with...

Best,

Based on discussion with John, I have an idea for implementing this in a staged manner, so we don't have to immediately commit to a new REST API.

Essentially, we would implement the new VIF Config classes and VIF Plugin class, but keep them inside Nova initially. We would create VIF plugin subclasses to deal with each of the current legacy VIF types. When Nova gets the VIF information from Neutron, it would convert it to the new VIF config class structure, and pick a suitable VIF plugin subclass to use.

This covers probably 98% of the Nova implementation work implied by this spec proposal. Crucially there would be no need to modify Neutron in any way during this process.

Once we've provide the design viable in terms of Nova impl, we can move the new objects out into the os-vif library as a stable API, and convert Neutron to use the new object model, and allow the new format data to be passed over the REST API.

So essentially we would have 2 phases

 - Liberty - do all the object design work and convert Nova code
 - Mita - declare the object design stable and convert Neutron."}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2015-07-01 12:15:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

(3 comments)

Dan's latest suggested approach makes sense to me. Count me in.

-jay"}, {'account_id': 13869, 'date': '2015-07-01 13:11:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Can we expect to have this stevedore mechanism in Nova for the Liberty release to load external VIFPlug implementation ? Or will it be only available in os-vif for the Mita release ?'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2015-07-01 13:18:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

In a 2-phase development model there would be no visible changes to Neutron or Neutron mechanisms - it would solely be a refactoring of Nova internals. So mechanisms would not gain the ability to provide custom plugins until the Mite release cycle. This is to allow Liberty cycle to prove the general design works well, before we commit to maintaining it as a stable API'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-07-02 21:21:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

In terms of progressive impl, I don't think there is much of interest to do in the external library - that is really mostly just the boring list of VIFConfig classes and the base plugin class API definition. I think the interesting code to prototype is actually the stuff that will be inside nova - ie the manner in which this integrates with the virt drivers and the provision of backcompatibility support for exiting VIF types. commit_message:
VIF port config versioned objects and driver plugin library

Define a standalone os-vif python library, inspired by os-brick,
to provide a versioned object model for data passed from neutron
to nova for VIF port binding, and an API to allow vendors to
provide custom plug/unplug actions for execution by Nova.

Blueprint: os-vif-library
Change-Id: If285dae9934cd21d58e52c15dedff9e68e418a47

os.urandom. It would fail because the result of urandom is a bunch

commit_message:
Fix unicode handling in get_random_string

get_random_string would often fail in decoding the result of
os.urandom. It would fail because the result of urandom is a bunch
of random bytes and not valid text (i.e., not a valid utf-8
representation).

Turns out that it's unnecessary to decode the result of os.urandom.
It returns six.binary_type whether on py2 or py3, and
binascii.hexlify() takes a six.binary_type as the argument.

binascii.hexlify() returns six.binary_type and we want
get_random_string() to return six.text_type, so convert.

Also, fixed the docstrings to use """.

Closes-Bug: 1514981
Change-Id: I60c31f2c47614beb3ed3c143d7815fdc15f5a0e0

commit_message:
Fix mistypes in english words

Affected:
  1. fuelweb_test/
       |- helpers/
         |- checkers.py                    : function  check_stats_private_info(...)
           -> dict private_data (was mistype at key 'keystone_ostf_password')
         |- ntp.py                         : class     Ntp
           -> added constructor (adding properties outside __init__ is bad practice)
         |- utils.py                       : class     timestat
           -> property spended_time was renamed to spent time
              and usage at system_test/helpers/decorators.py at method step_start_stop (line 44)
              was updated as dependency
       |- tests/
         |- plugins/
           |- test_fuel_plugin_contrail.py : class     ContrailPlugin
             -> globals _add_ub_packag & _add_cen_packag waf renamed with dependencies
         |- tests_separate_services/
           |- test_separate_horison.py     : class SeparateHorison
             -> in method separate_horison_service, call self.fuel_web.update_nodes: mistype at 2nd parameter dict
                (stabdalone-horizon -> standalone-horizon)
         |- base_test_case.py              : class     TestBasic(object)
           -> self._test.program -> create at __init__ with value None and process it at test_program property
              (was creation in property (outside __init__()))
       |- test_jumbo_frames.py             : class     TestJumboFrames
         -> added __init__() for creating os_conn field

  2. Comments and log outputs was updated
  3. Some parts of code was reformatted to follow PEP8 (binary operation in if's)
  4. Shadowed builtins (id -> osd_id|release_id and etc)
Update reason: rebase

Related-Bug: #1513777

Change-Id: Ifc153b97e168e80cc149851357aa14f0b221db22

commit_message:
Fixes Broken Error Message on Subnet Creation

Wrong key used for getting the name and id of network in the case of
it not being passed into the method call.
This fixes the key used.

Change-Id: I6757a946be4696027befbe98b490881e967e80eb
Closes-Bug:1505414

commit_message:
More instructions for neutron-db-manage revision --autogenerate

More detailed instructions for --autogenerate, including how to rely
less on devstack. Also some tweaks to scripts and requirements to
simplify the process.

Closes-Bug: #1197570

Change-Id: I97043b30a8df7408a73af38c6a015fc0dcf82571

commit_message:
Directive to check if policy check passes

A directive to check for policies. If it passes, the contents enclosed are
shown to the user, otherwise it will remain hidden.

Change-Id: I41607f587641927e2f77ae50625d92959d6d541e
Partial-Bug: #1450150

commit_message:
Remove unnecessary destroy call from Ironic virt driver

To give some context, calling destroy [5] was added as a
bug fix [1]. It was required back then because, Nova compute
was not calling destroy on catching the exception [2]. But now,
Nova compute catches all exceptions that happen during spawn
and calls destroy (_shutdown_instance) [3]

Since Nova compute is already taking care of destroying the
instance before rescheduling, we shouldn't have to call destroy
separately in the driver. I confirmed in logs that destroy gets
called twice if there is any failure during
_wait_for_active() [4] or timeout happens [5]

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/99519/
[2] https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/2014.1.5/nova/compute/manager.py#L2116-L2118
[3] https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/2015.1.2/nova/compute/manager.py#L2472-L2497
[4] https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/2015.1.2/nova/virt/ironic/driver.py#L359-L384
[5] https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/2015.1.2/nova/virt/ironic/driver.py#L730-L741

Closes-Bug: #1506234

Change-Id: I09da7910befc4167d9cf043d12b19432ed70bcac

commit_message:
Add .DS_Store to .gitignore

.DS_Store is the name of a file in the Apple OS X operating
system for storing custom attributes of a folder such as the
position of icons or the choice of a background image.

Change-Id: Icfc775a63de6672967b91e0540e13a3a327b5bf8

commit_message:
Don't expect NST to be specified in a cluster

Nailgun apparently does not include information about network
segmentation type to JSON representations of environments for
GET and POST requests.

This patch removes all references to that information.

Closes-bug: #1514897
Change-Id: I0d7970ad4c45c4e6175a7366610df1ec2a850254

Opened up wireshark.

While find_image is running, there's constant traffic between the client and the glance endpoint.

Then, after some time there's a packet from keystone and everything stops - probably because the token expired? Anyway, once that happens it's just hung and not doing anything, so this is probably a bug to file in openstacksdk.

I'm going to take a wild guess here and say that find_image is running some sort of network-using-call on every image, which has never been tested on a cloud with a large number of images and/or a cloud at 230ms latency."}, {'account_id': 17098, 'date': '2015-10-14 09:51:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: -Code-Review

Sort rpm/deb files alphabetically

This is rather trivial, but it makes comparing the files much easier

commit_message:
Allow screen without logging to disk

In some niche setups it is desirable to run OpenStack services under
screen, but undesirable to automatically keep a persistent log from
each service.

Add a new variable SCREEN_IS_LOGGING that controls if screen logs each
window to disk automatically.

Ideally screen itself would be configured to log but just not activate.
This isn't possible with the screerc syntax.  Temporary logging can still
be used by a developer with:
    C-a : logfile foo
    C-a : log on

Change-Id: I2a3abf15dea95ae99ddbdfe1309382df601b7d93

commit_message:
Add firewall detail actions and breadcrumb nav

This patch adds the standard table row actions to firewalls, along with
basic breadcrumb navigation.

Also makes minor changes to workflow step titles and adds missing
translation to the Ports breadcrumb.

Change-Id: I3941d8ae8b75ecd1e85b4f140f24aa0f8eddb5cc
Closes-Bug: 1457437
Partial-Bug: 1413823

commit_message:
MongoDB elements switch to YAML

MongoDB 3.0.7 changed the default conf layout to use YAML. The elements
modify this file and so need updating.

Change-Id: I2c3ae3ac719d35c0a34bf8c64bbb8cc8aed01ad5
Closes-Bug: bug/1506979

If the user specifies an array of more than one allocation pool for the
neutron_subnet allocation_pool parameter, the order of the pools is not
guaranteed. On sequential puppet runs, puppet may error with "Property

commit_message:
Map allocation_pool property to set

If the user specifies an array of more than one allocation pool for the
neutron_subnet allocation_pool parameter, the order of the pools is not
guaranteed. On sequential puppet runs, puppet may error with "Property
allocation_pools does not support being updated" because the array is
read in a different order. To avoid this, define the insync? method to
compare the values as though they were unordered sets rather than
ordered lists.

Change-Id: I9c146b5abe563c7e6ebfed169e770ffe8e5cf94b

commit_message:
EC: Use best available ec_type in unittests

To minimize external library dependencies for Swift unit
tests and SAIO, PyECLib 1.1.1 introduces a native backend
'liberasurecode_rs_vand.'  This patch is to migrate over
the unit tests to the new ec_type when available.

This change will work with current pyeclib requirements
(==1.0.7) and also future requirements (>=1.0.7).

When we're able to raise *our* requirements to >=1.1.1 we
should remove jerasure from the list of preferred backends.
Related SAIO doc and example config changes should be
included with that patch.

Co-Authored-By: Clay Gerrard <clay.gerrard@gmail.com>
Change-Id: Idf657f0acf0479bc8158972e568a29dbc08eaf3b

commit_message:
Fix Python 3 issues in dashboard image tests

* Use NamedTemporaryFile instead of TemporaryFile because we must
  have a name which is a text on Python 3. Otherwise, the test fails.
  On Python 3, TemporaryFile uses an integer for the file name, the
  file descriptor.
* Replace filter() and map() with list comprehensions to get a list
  on Python 3.
* On Python 3, temporary files are open in binary mode so write a
  byte string instead of a text string.
* tox.ini: enable all image tests on Python 3.

Partial-Implements: blueprint porting-python3
Change-Id: Ice7f119c040bbddeda10ed45d137bb7851764b8d

commit_message:
Port network topology tests to Python 3

Replace json.loads() with oslo_serialization.jsonutils.loads() to
accept bytes (HTTP body). jsonutils.loads() decodes the HTTP body
from UTF-8.

tox.ini: add network_topology tests to Python 3.

Change-Id: I9f65d63e3ed54525e52b92b7728b78cf1b9e7bb5

commit_message:
Port dashboard stack tests to Python 3

* On Python 3, the pretty JSON output doesn't add space before newline.
* CreateStackForm: don't compare str to int, it raises a TypeError on
  Python 3. Instead, use MinLength already converted to int.
* tox.ini: enable all stacks on Python 3.

Partial-Implements: blueprint porting-python3
Change-Id: I20cd9e83720cc3974973bec5471864f0ffc00716

commit_message:
suppress warning output in a unit test

test_write_builder_after_device_removal() wasn't setting a
default min_part_hours so a warnign was printed. Explicitly
adding a min_part_hours suppresses the warning

Change-Id: I6f234b72c34e066abb91f28e6eacf50e29be8842

commit_message:
Add exception unit tests with different message types

There were no unit tests that showed what happened when the custom
message to an UnexpectedError is an exception or a binary string.
There's plenty of places in keystone where the custom message is
set to an exception.

Change-Id: Ib2c51ff41a8b720c7fd0486c2cf90ddc0c54d065

commit_message:
Fix scheduler compatibility with Python 3.7

Always catch StopIteration, rather than allowing it to bubble up a level.
This is neccessary due to PEP0479, wherein it was decided that Python will
start converting this exception to a RuntimeError when it bubbles up,
beginning with Python 3.7.

Change-Id: I4e93b0e85500455de415188cc679961035958bd1

commit_message:
Block oslo.messaging 2.8.0

Released on 11/9, there has been a spike in timeout failures in
nova unit/functional test jobs that rely on in-memory RPC from
oslo.messaging.

From local testing it sounds like d700c38279 is the issue.

Change-Id: I37eeb57e99db5f77a11eed471ac6c55c4547e821
Related-Bug: #1514876

commit_message:
Support for SSL protocol and cipher controls

Add ability to explicitly specify SSL/TLS protocol
version and ciphers. We add 2 string options and
do not specify any default for backward compatability.
If the values are not specified explicitly we fall
back to the python defaults as we did before.

DocImpact

Closes-Bug: #1513581
Change-Id: I149cf569e1e5277f30e89203d20731d4482509d4

you can't run dockerbuild command

Setting `show_image_direct_url` to true allows to enable Copy-On-Write
features when using some storage backends across Nova, Cinder & Glance.
It allows for example nearly instantaneous creation of instances root
disk and volumes when using RBD as a storage backend for all projects by

'}]
commit_message:
Enable glance-api show_image_direct_url for COW

Setting `show_image_direct_url` to true allows to enable Copy-On-Write
features when using some storage backends across Nova, Cinder & Glance.
It allows for example nearly instantaneous creation of instances root
disk and volumes when using RBD as a storage backend for all projects by
using Ceph features instead of downloading from Ceph via Glance, then
convert the image, then upload to Ceph via Nova or Cinder.

Change-Id: I1f56273c6b7c8d3922799cae07a66eebc0884205

commit_message:
Align some defaults with with ControllerCount default

NeutronDhcpAgentsPerNetwork is normally correlated with the
number of controllers, so given that the template
defaults the ControllerCount to 1, 1 seems like a more consistent
value for NeutronDhcpAgentsPerNetwork, and it's consistent with
what we test in CI.

Also NeutronL3HA defaults to False, which is consistent with the default
ControllerCount of 1, but NeutronAllowL3AgentFailover defaults to
True, which I assume makes no sense if there's only 1 controller
and no HA

Change-Id: I4612060979d1e4381800f30e359f58aeef61b861

commit_message:
Check subnetpool extension support

This fix is to add support for checking subnetpool extension support
at Kuryr server startup time. If required extension is found missing,
startup script will exit and kuryr driver server will not start.

Change-Id: I264be36c1b3b23517f4f2ff741f51a5a86b2ae9f
Closes-Bug: #1498393

commit_message:
Add bay filter to resource api

Add bay filter to resource api, so that we can filter resource by
bay_ident.

Change-Id: Ic355b8c40cd7cf9d65d6d62fae5761ef977fbf6c
Partially-Implements: blueprint filter-resource-by-bay

I chatted with Daisy yesterday and a question was raised.
Do we really need to support multiple documents like openstack-manuals?
Doesn't a single document style work as most projects do?"}, {'account_id': 10497, 'date': '2015-11-06 06:07:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

hm, okay. I'll update the docs as a single doc."}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2015-11-06 07:08:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Kato-san, can we talk on #-i18n channel?

I think there are several points to be considered:
- a single document or multiple documents
- document translation handling (we can leverage docs tool chain)
- document style checking like niceness (I think docs tool chain is useful)

We need to consider a balance.

My -1 is just because we need to clarify the direction.'}, {'account_id': 10497, 'date': '2015-11-06 08:26:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 10497, 'date': '2015-11-06 09:16:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Patch Set 6 was rebased'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-06 09:16:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Verified+1

/FYI/ 
document publish (to docs.o.o) is usually done by {name}-docs job [1].
{name}-docs jenkins job is defined at [2] and the actual script is [3].
As you find the comment at [3], python setup.py build_sphinx is intentionally used.

- [1] http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack-infra/project-config/tree/zuul/layout.yaml#n361
- [2] http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack-infra/project-config/tree/jenkins/jobs/openstack-publish-jobs.yaml#n2
- [3] http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack-infra/project-config/tree/jenkins/scripts/run-docs.sh#n15'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2015-11-09 06:47:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

commit_message:
Set up the initial documentation infra

This commit adds tox.ini and define test targets.
Naming of tox targets follows OpenStack most projects:
- docs for document generation

For mainly a testing purpose, contributor-guide/source/index.rst
includes CONTRIBUTING.rst at the top level.
To generate the current doc, run "tox -e docs".

setup.py and setup.cfg are added because they are
required to publish the docs to docs.o.o.

Co-Authored-By: Akihiro Motoki <amotoki@gmail.com>
Implements: blueprint i18n-contributor-guide
Change-Id: Iaf3b09865ced8b30f987b68a07c2970d2b425708

commit_message:
Removed old k8s python client

The old k8s client is no longer used. Magnum uses a newer version of
k8s client right now, which is located at
magnum/common/pythonk8sclient/swagger_client.

Closes-Bug: #1515039
Change-Id: I1dbe4c4cb80b50247f90b9d005939515dcb1da32

commit_message:
Catch exceptions for restore_prev_rsrc/prepare_for_replace

Catch exceptions when calling restore_prev_rsrc or
prepare_for_replace, to make sure the failure will be
recorded and the resource will put into FAILED state.

Closes-Bug: #1512496
(cherry picked from commit 96f7c545ee069debcc22f25770aa0c351ec0ee7c)

Conflicts:
	heat/engine/resource.py
	heat/tests/test_resource.py

Change-Id: If65953d6b8cbdc135d898119c0f43a133f2e1892

commit_message:
Fix mixin class clients

In patch I78b57d44b37c34cebadc2b72cf55b4f9405447a3
was added new clients methods for keystone resources.
As result it leads to error when we try to use role_assignments
properties.

Change-Id: I127863ee37f2cba487d6c66ec12a0035319f3fc2
Closes-Bug: #1509333
(cherry picked from commit 6621d64da7efc8e4f3c40f6d99f612a110b7b471)

commit_message:
Follow up patch for 8c3e102fc5736bfcf98525ebab59b6598a69b428

This patch is a follow up patch fixing some nits left by the review
8c3e102fc5736bfcf98525ebab59b6598a69b428.

is set

tests

commit_message:
Fix purging of raw_template rows

Templates referenced in the prev_raw_template_id column of the stack
table are not filtered by the purge_deleted script and end up being
removed. This fixes it by making sure that we consider them when
filtering.

Change-Id: I8bab657dfe77b7cef5971e370f6b4f9825a22ba8
Closes-Bug: #1506079
(cherry picked from commit 78d5c425d0a5573de187c83705f4b6c034fc441d)

commit_message:
Resource.has_interface check get_resource_info result

This changes the behaviour of has_interface to not assume that
get_resource_info always returns a type. There are circumstances when it
won't, such as when the type is no longer in the new registry during a
stack update.

Change-Id: Idd9dade85d105dc6839ff0740e6c80aca6b7ad9f
Closes-Bug: #1509880
(cherry picked from commit af3355d34c8b8e4030f7a928a6c7cb9ad70e0795)
