commit_message:
StackUser tolerate missing user on delete

If a stack domain user is missing on delete, we currently fail to
delete the keypair.  We should tolerate this in a simiar way to
that done for _delete_user.

Change-Id: I6d60612e6187385a2d3b6b6fcf67acb99b572fc3
Closes-Bug: #1505981
(cherry picked from commit 730ccc5abf6dd5e133578b4b7fbef32e3b64fe14)

Assert has_calls in tests

Instead of assert_has_calls, tests were wrongly using has_calls.

Corrected the same in this patch.

Also fix bugs in corresponding functions.

When an IPMI password consists only of numbers, Ironic fails to create a
password file. From the format point of view, these passwords are
correct. These are that it is stored to the variable after being
converted to an int type, cause errors in the subsequent processing to
expect that it is a string type.
This bug has been fixed in the master, but there is still in liberty,
it will be fixed in this patch.

commit_message:
Fix a bug error by passwords only includes numbers

When an IPMI password consists only of numbers, Ironic fails to create a
password file. From the format point of view, these passwords are
correct. These are that it is stored to the variable after being
converted to an int type, cause errors in the subsequent processing to
expect that it is a string type.
This bug has been fixed in the master, but there is still in liberty,
it will be fixed in this patch.

Change-Id: Id7d88715e439f93693f5153b0a4cf0c2023afd86
Related-Bug: #1489234

commit_message:
Scrub orphan mappings pre-migration on source

Live migration can fail if orphan mappings associated with the migrating
LPAR exist on the source system.

This change set exploits the recently-added
pypowervm.tasks.storage.ScrubOrphanStorageForLpar, which will identify
such mappings for a specified LPAR ID, scrub them, and (for VSCSI
mappings) remove the associated storage if it is not still in use.

Change-Id: I747ad4063ebd5cb4effc565a4d255e325d454ffb

2. I've not tested it beyond making sure that I can hit the API with these changes; i.e. this hasn't broken something that I've known to work in the past, I haven't really exercised whether the proposed change actually has the intended effect.

3. Does this require any updates to the Trove documentation? After all, there's a change to the file trove.conf.

commit_message:
Added CORS middleware to Trove

This adds the CORS support middleware to Trove, allowing a deployer
to optionally configure rules under which a javascript client may
break the single-origin policy and access the API directly.

For trove, the paste.ini method of deploying the middleware was
chosen, because it needs to be able to annotate responses created
by keystonemiddleware. If the middleware were explicitly included
as in the previous patch, keystone would reject the request before
the cross-domain headers could be annotated, resulting in an
error response that was unreadable by the user agent.

OpenStack Spec:
   http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/openstack-specs/specs/cors-support.html
Oslo_Middleware Docs:
   http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.middleware/cors.html
Cloud Admin Guide Documentation:
   http://docs.openstack.org/admin-guide-cloud/cross_project_cors.html

Change-Id: Ic55305607e44069d893baf2a261d5fe7da777303

commit_message:
Migrate kerberos plugin

The auth plugin from the keystoneclient-kerberos repository is
copied to this package. It was in its own repository because it
requires the requests-kerberos package and we want to minimize
requirements in keystoneauth (or keystoneclient at the time the
plugin was originally developed). Since we've got support for
"extras" in setup.cfg in pip now this isn't an issue with the
package anymore. Users of the kerberos plugin must install the
extra packages using

 $ pip install keystoneauth['kerberos']

otherwise the plugin will fail to load.

Closes-Bug: 1512741
Change-Id: Ia84bf559413e9bfd1a3faaceb417c2477bd10d5f

commit_message:
Support .zip and .csar extension for CSAR files

Support .csar as well as .zip for input CSAR files.
Add unit tests to verify that both .zip and .csar
extensions are validated and parsed properly.

Change-Id: I9d531ceb0e2e1bd36817692677dcbf2b5d5520a9
Closes-Bug: #1506163

commit_message:
Add docstring validation

This introduces a linter for PEP257 to avoid trivial nitpicking of
docstrings in code reviews. Because flake8_docstrings simply provides a
plugin to add pep257 to flake8, you can run it via `tox -e pep8`.

PEP257 checks which we are currently violating are ignored in tox.ini.
We can remove them from the ignored list as they are fixed.

Change-Id: I01ebad7b70cf61dd80d3c06c6808d8178fbdd634
Related-Bug: 1501544
Depends-On: I60adf0dca4aa32f4ef6bca61250b375c8a3703c6

commit_message:
Make Monasca Java API bind interface configurable

Use $SERVICE_HOST if it exists for Monasca Java API
interface to bind to.

Change-Id: Iea516001a4bbda6d825bbdb7d3c91a5018eba045

commit_message:
Allow customization of the Ceph pool names

This is useful in those scenarios were we want to use an external
Ceph deployment with multiple overclouds.

Change-Id: I1749d2a6547f6ce25843709e46a1447e8d42cfff

Fix simport requirement

Make simport requirement be =>0.2.dev16. This works
when installing Monasca Notification in the DevStack
Plugin.

Resync nodepool.yaml with system-config version.

to include the recent change merged in system-config

commit_message:
Redhat-family support for PostgreSQL

Provides Redhat support for PgSQL and makes it easy to extend
further to support other linux variants.

Currently, config.template files for the various datastores are
rendered by the task manager and sent to the guest agent. For
databases such as PostgreSQL that may have OS-specific config
entries, the most appropriate place to render portions of the
config template is on the guest itself.

The template generated by the task manager will therefore leave
any guest-specific elements intact so that they can be rendered
in a second pass by the datastore.

Once the pgsql guest receives the template, it replaces the OS
specific entries. The same logic is also used to 'render'
previously hardcoded constants for things like the location of
the postgresql.conf and pg_hba.conf files.

Change-Id: Ie6906b8040e863abdc1cdabd244b530d46ab6dc5
Depends-On: Iec015b75d6f06787043bae63f170bb45cef1158b
closes-bug: #1442387

commit_message:
Update zuul-dev.o.o pipelines

zuul-dev is for testing only so we set all zuul-dev pipelines
to low priority.  We also want to update zuul-dev pipelines
to match zuul pipeline configurations.

Change-Id: I392496d2d48952fe2eac24e1ebcdf1aea0721e06

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-10 19:18:17.000000000', 'message': 'Fix chart data loading

Recently we noticed that the charts on the first page were not being
loaded once the data was retrieved from the API. This was happening due
to controller variables being empty once it was instantiated.

Moving the assignment of these variables to happen inside the controller
method ensures the chart will only be loaded once they are available.

Change-Id: Ief661046d1647e1084c3b9f5eb43a6596e6f058e
'}]
commit_message:
Fix chart data loading

Recently we noticed that the charts on the first page were not being
loaded once the data was retrieved from the API. This was happening due
to controller variables being empty once it was instantiated.

Moving the assignment of these variables to happen inside the controller
method ensures the chart will only be loaded once they are available.

Change-Id: Ief661046d1647e1084c3b9f5eb43a6596e6f058e

commit_message:
Added ICMP 'type' and 'code' checking capability to 'netutils' module

ICMP has 'type' and 'code' fields which are used while adding a security
group rule using Horizon. I have written functions in 'netutils' module
which validate ICMP 'type' and 'code' fields.

Change-Id: Ie1a67ea1afd69d5de4326f9e9a7243362b912582
Closes-Bug: #1511940

commit_message:
Separate setting catalog on headers from others

A minor cleanup to make setting catalog headers distinct from the
regular headers. This makes it easier to see the difference between the
headers that are set for the service token and the user token as we only
set service catalog for user token.

Change-Id: I696e826a9983965258cf4cf518ab399723d27649

commit_message:
Allowing for shares to be edited on an existing cluster

Now allowing the shares parameter to be passed on
a cluster update call.  It is optional and defaults to
None.

Change-Id: I1a16bff7bd3d20a4253a66bedc86d8c1c72328a6
Partial-Implements: bp sahara-add-shares-to-clusters
Depends-On: I33971eb495c5a318ba17a4b3f98534b9e8776deb

So... One important piece missing in this summary is the fact that a significant part of Monasca is written in Java. I can see bits of Python everywhere, so could you clarify what's the situation here ?

For the record, I don't object to adding languages when the technical benefit outweighs the community cost. In particular, when the language achieves something the already-supported languages can't achieve (think Javascript). But when the language is just added for convenience of adopting an existing code base, we have to consider the costs to our community. Beyond the load on the infrastructure team (which is still working to fully support Javascript in addition to Python), I'm worried about our community fragmentation. We are struggling to maintain a common culture, which is what makes us "OpenStack", and the Big Tent further increases the tension. 

Adding a language creates a de-facto silo inside our community: those that are able (or willing) to touch that language. Of the top Monasca contributors in Liberty, *none* have been contributing to any other OpenStack project. As a community today, we don't need anything that creates more silos, we need more people caring about OpenStack as a whole. We need more people to step up to help on horizontal functions, like Infra, QA tooling, Release management, Security. I see supporting an additional language as additional load on all those teams, not accompanied by any new resource from the silo sub-community. I see it as further fragmenting a community that is already struggling with its identity and culture. This would be a huge cost, and one that I'm probably not ready to pay just to add a new monitoring solution to the big tent.

But maybe everything is just being rewritten in Python and this is a non-issue. So could you clarify that point ?'}, {'account_id': 12512, 'date': '2015-08-17 14:38:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 15799, 'date': '2015-08-17 15:12:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 16979, 'date': '2015-08-17 15:29:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 11809, 'date': '2015-08-17 18:45:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi Thierry, I am one of the top contributors to Monasca and I also contribute to OpenStack by reviewing new projects for the openstack-infra. It may not be glamorous, but I like to think that it helps.'}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2015-08-17 20:30:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi Thierry, We have completed ports to Python for the Monasca API and the Monasca Persister and have attained complete functional parity. Python is the go forward language for the project and we will be completely transitioning to Python.

The Notification Engine (monasca-notification repo) was originally written in Python.

The Monasca API (monasca-api repo) was originally written in Java and has been completely ported to Python. In the monasca-api repo there is a sub-directory, monasca_api, that contains all the Python code. 

The Monasca Persister (monasca-persister repo) was originally written in Java and has been completely ported to Python. In the monasca-persister repo there is a sub-directory, monasca_persister, that contains all the Python code for the Persister.

The Monasca Common (monasca-common repo) was originally written in Java. Right now we are in the process of adding a sub-directory to monasca_common, which will have some common Python code between the various Python components in Monasca.

The Python Monasca Client (python-monascaclient), Monasca to Ceilometer (monasca-ceilometer), Monasca Agent (monasca-agent) and Monasca Statsd (monasca-statsd) are all written in Python. All Python components are in Pypi, https://pypi.python.org/pypi?%3Aaction=search&term=monasca&submit=search

The Monasca Threshold Engine is the only remaining component that has not been ported to Python yet. The Threshold Engine is a little more complicated than other components. We use a technology called Apache Storm to build a real-time streaming, in-memory, scalable, distributed and fault-tolerant threshold engine. Similar technologies were not available in Python when we wrote the Threshold Engine and this space tends to be driven by Java technologies, such as Apache Samza and Apache Spark. Performance in the Threshold Engine is also critical. Currently, we have started to develop  a Threshold Engine in Python. We are evaluating a stand-alone Python Threshold Engine, which I've started work on,  as well as use of Apache Spark and Spark Streaming, which supports Python and has recently reached a level of maturity at which it could be considered a viable platform and replacement. Writing a Threshold Engine in Python is not that difficult, but developing one that it is performant, efficient, scalable, distributed and fault-tolerant involves a bit of work and we would like to build a real replacement for the current one.

Most new development in Monasca is in Python. For example, all the work on the Monasca Events processing system is in Python.

Currently, we are in the process of transitioning to Python. As a consequence, we maintain both code bases where applicable. In the short-term, I see most of the work on the Java code as primarily bug fixes, maintenance and small improvements. There could be several features that we add to the Java code, but in that case we will ensure that the Python code stays in sync, which is what we've been doing so far. Over-time, new features will get added to the Python code, and will not be added to the Java code. For example, the events processing system is in Python. We are also in the process of adding Apache Cassandra as a supported database in Monasca, and that work will only be done on the Python API and Persister. At some point the transition to Python will be complete, and the Java code will be deprecated.

As Craig Bryant has mentioned, we have members on the Monasca team that are quite active in reviews in the OpenStack Infra, so we are also trying to play a role in the broader community, and I think that role will grow.

In general, I think we are doing everything we can to bring Monasca forward into the OpenStack community. Please let me know if you have any further questions or issues."}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-08-18 09:08:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Roland: Thanks for the clarification! If the long-term plan is to have everything in Python, that certainly alleviates most of my concerns about community fragmentation. For the bits that have been completely ported to Python, is there a plan to phase out Java code ? Requiring that people have a dual Python+Java proficiency to propose changes that affect both "sides" of the code at the same time sounds also quite restrictive.

@Craig: Reviews on infra definitely help! Thanks for your work there.

Other question, looking at the recent commits I see a lot of rather terse commit messages like "Fix bug jah-1669" (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/190805/) which seem to only reference some private JIRA instance. That sounds very much non-OpenStack -- what are the plans to improve on that front ?'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-08-18 09:13:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Roland: Re-reading myself I realize my question about the plan to deprecate Java code in unclear. I mean, is it possible to deprecate java code in the completely-ported components without waiting for the rest of the components to be fully ported ? Or can the not-yet-ported java components only work with the java version of other components ?'}, {'account_id': 12512, 'date': '2015-08-18 13:24:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Thierry: In regards to terse commit messages that reference internal bug tracking systems, we have informed our team members that from now on, we will be strictly adhering to the OpenStack Commit message standards found here https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages. This should not be an issue moving forward.'}, {'account_id': 12512, 'date': '2015-08-18 13:44:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Thierry: In addition to informing committers about proper commit guidelines, the PTL and the core members will ensure, from here on, that all commits adhere to the commit guidelines before approving.'}, {'account_id': 11094, 'date': '2015-08-18 14:30:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2015-08-18 17:49:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Thierry: There is no requirement in Monasca to develop in both Java and Python simultaneously. 

For all the components that are pure Python, then it is easy to develop in Python. 

For the two components that have both Java and Python implementations, the Monasca API and Monasca Persister, if a new feature is being added, and someone doesn't want to do that development in Java, then it only needs to be implemented in Python. For example,  we are only adding RBAC and support for Cassandra to the Python code. This implies that the Python implementation could diverge from the Java implementation, but that is OK as that is the direction for the project. New features serve as an incentive to move.

The only case where programming in both Java and Python is required is if a new feature is being added to the Java code. In this case then it is a requirement that the new feature be implemented in the Python code. Additionally, if we found a bug or performance issue in the Java code, and the same issue was in the Python code, we would obviously carry the fix forward to the Python code. The organizations that would be primarily interested in doing this are the one's already developing and deploying Monasca, and they are already proficient in Java and Python. For anyone new to Monasca who is only interested in Python, then this isn't necessary, and their focus can remain on the Python code.

For the Threshold Engine, since it is only in Java right now, to work on that component requires Java expertise. Note, we don't do too much development in the Threshold Engine ourselves. However, as I mentioned, we're looking to move to Python in this area, and it seems to me like more of an opportunity if anything to develop a new Python Threshold Engine. Incidentally, we just met with several members of the Ceilometer team, and there is work in progress in developing a streaming alarm engine. The current Ceilometer alarm engine polls the API. We will investigate further and discuss if this is a good area for collaboration.

All the Python and Java components are compatible. You can mix and match Java and Python today. For example, you can run the Python Monasca API with the Java Monasca Persister. The API doesn't communicate with the Persister in any capacity, and the only exchange is via publishing/consuming messages via the Message Queue. Message schemas are the same.

As I've stated, our go forward language for Monasca is Python. 

To address your concern above regarding needing to be proficient in Java and Python, I don't really see any barriers to a Python only developer becoming involved with the Monasca project."}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-08-18 19:44:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

@Roland: thanks for the precisions, it really helps me understand where you stand and where you're headed.

You say "All the Python and Java components are compatible. You can mix and match Java and Python today." -- I guess my remaining question then is why are you keeping the Java code in the components that have already been fully ported in Python ?'}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2015-08-18 20:30:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Thierry Currently, Monasca is in transition from Java to Python. There are a couple of reasons that we are temporarily keeping the Java components that we have ported to Python. There are already organizations that are using the Monasca Java components in production. We need to continue to support them with bug fixes and performance enhancements. There may even be small feature enhancements, but I don't think that will be common. Switching to the new Python implementation involves change, and we need to do this transition in a well tested and coordinated fashion with all the organizations involved. After those transitions have been completed, the Java code will deprecated, and probably removed from the repo. Our current plan is to keep the Monasca repositories organized as they are, with the Python and Java code co-located, as we think it makes this transition smoother and more manageable."}, {'account_id': 11605, 'date': '2015-08-18 20:32:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thierry-  as an operator running Monasca in production, i am not yet ready to bite the bullet and switch over to some of the new Python components until we have had an opportunity to test them at scale.  Hence the need to have both for some period of time'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-08-19 09:25:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

OK, I totally get that the installed base needs time to migrate to a Python-only world, and that you need to keep the Java code around for some time. I guess the two versions could be stored in separate repositories, since they are not consumed at the same time, but that's more a detail."}, {'account_id': 12512, 'date': '2015-08-19 16:32:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I think this community has been chugging along and growing. This project does have a diversity challenge - http://stackalytics.com/?project_type=stackforge&module=monasca-group&metric=commits though not quite as bad as some others we have added recently.

I would like to specifically comment on the Java question. Blocking a thing because it has Java in it seems pretty silly at this point. We've got projects that include Python, Javascript, and Go. We have projects that depend on services written in Erlang, C, C++, Java, Go (and probably others). To continue to pretend to draw this firm line on "must be python" seems academic at this point. A working OpenStack is not just the python glue layer, it's the whole thing. To debug these kinds of environments people already need some ability to address issues at all of these layers.'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2015-08-25 19:06:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'm a little worried that https://launchpad.net/monasca says meetings are held on vidyo

is that still true?"}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2015-08-25 19:49:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi Doug, We've been hosting meetings in video conferencing and minutes are usually taken. Information on Monasca meetings and minutes is at, https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Meetings/Monasca. Meetings are completely open to anyone. Note, just last week, we moved from Vidyo to WebEX, hosted by Cisco and I forgot to update the Launchpad link. 

To address your concern about meetings being held via video conferencing and not in IRC. This has been a topic that we've discussed several times. Most recently, we discussed this at the Monasca Mid-cycle meetup a few weeks ago. Minutes from that session are at, https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/monasca_liberty_mid_cycle_tent.

What we said is the following:

If WebEx is not acceptable to community, then will switch completely to IRC. Note, currently it appears like the attendees of the Monasca weekly meeting would like to continue with using a video conferencing solution.

If that is not acceptable, then we can move to IRC immediately.

Does that address your concern?"}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2015-08-25 20:05:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1 Rollcall-Vote+1'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2015-08-25 21:04:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Rollcall-Vote-1

(1 comment)

a) I have no problem at all with code that uses Java instead of Python. None at all.

b) I have no problem with (indeed, I encourage) competing solutions for a problem domain.

c) I have no problem with (indeed, I encourage) competing implementations of the same OpenStack RESTful API.

d) I have a big problem with the severe overlap of Monasca's RESTful API with that of the OpenStack Telemetry API. There seems to have been no effort to effect change in the OpenStack Telemetry API that were desired by the Monasca operators and developers. Instead, a RESTful API was built that overlaps 95% of the functionality of the OpenStack Telemetry API and looks almost the same (but for some reason is slightly different) as the OpenStack Telemetry API.

What this means, unless someone corrects me and tells me that Monasca is **not** a telemetry and metric collection/storage service, is that OpenStack will now have two slightly different OpenStack Telemetry APIs. Imagine if we had 2 OpenStack Compute APIs, both purporting to do the same things, but that required users to use different API calls to do the same thing? That is precisely what we're going to introduce if this goes through as it stands here.

e) The Ceilometer project has learned a lesson over the last few years that doing both metrics **and** alarms in the same API and service implementation was a bad idea. Monasca seems to be taking a similar path in having a single service that does both. Have the Monasca contributors considered this?

Best,

-jay"}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2015-08-25 22:26:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

As a cross-project person for docs, I get concerned about adding multiple layers of projects that won't necessarily have all the same tooling for docs, tests, builds, and so on. I say this as someone who had a maven toolset in stackforge that is now unmaintained. So while I do want to welcome more languages and skillsets to the OpenStack governance, I believe you have a harder row to hoe so to speak and want to be sure you're aware of that. For example, docs tooling is mainly Python based. Are you ready to be on your own for docs if you chose tools outside of the "self-service docs" model we're working towards?'}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2015-08-26 03:19:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Ann: Good question on the documentation. We are in the process of transitioning from Java to Python. All the components, except for the Monasca Threshold Engine have been ported to Python. We are also planning on porting the Threshold Engine too, but that component is a little more complicated. There was an earlier discussion in the comments above that provides more details of the state of Python in Monasca.

As we complete the transition to Python, we will also transition to using the OpenStack document toolchain and "self-service docs" model.'}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2015-08-26 04:41:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Jay: The requirement for a completely compatible API hasn't been articulated to us so far. Maybe this should be a discussion to have in the governance meeting in a couple of weeks when we discuss Monasca again?

There is a certain degree of cohesion between alarms and metrics, as alarms are defined on metrics. However, I think we've achieved a good balance between cohesion and loose coupling in the Monasca architecture. I sometimes describe Monasca as a micro-services message bus based architecture.

Referring to the architecture diagram at, https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Monasca#Architecture, the various components in Monasca are outlined. The API, Persister, Threshold Engine and Notification are independent components that reside in separate repos and are largely decoupled. They can be deployed together or independently. For example, there is no dependency between the Notification Engine and Persister, and you don't need to deploy the Notification Engine or Threshold Engine with Monasca if you are interested in only storing and retrieving time-series data. Or you could choose to go the other direction and only deploy the Threshold Engine, without the Persister and Notification Engine, or several other combinations.

To address your concern, "Monasca seems to be taking a similar path in having a single service that does both." where both is alarms and metrics. I don't really see it that way, as Monasca is really a distinct set of components and services.

Would it be worthwhile to do an architectural and design walkthrough of Monasca to go into more detail?'}, {'account_id': 7052, 'date': '2015-08-26 23:22:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@JayPipes. Monasca main concern is monitoring and not telemetry. Ceilometer API only provides info related to Openstack resources where instead Monasca is focussing on monitoring the underlining infrastructure allowing integration of logs, collectd, statsd (+ others) and libvirt.
Hope this clarifies your concern.'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-08-29 20:43:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

JAY, where in the criteria for the big tent is there an api clause?  https://github.com/openstack/governance/blob/master/resolutions/20141202-project-structure-reform-spec.rst'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2015-08-30 16:37:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Joe, there isn't any mention of API functional overlap in the project inclusion guidelines. I believe there should be.

Best,

-jay

p.s. How's pinterest?"}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2015-08-30 16:57:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Roland,

Thanks for your reply to my review, appreciated.

Some comments...

"The requirement for a completely compatible API hasn't been articulated to us so far. Maybe this should be a discussion to have in the governance meeting in a couple of weeks when we discuss Monasca again?"

Sure, as Joe points out, there is no requirement for API compatibility in the project inclusion guidelines. I believe there *should* be. However, I am not voting this down solely because of that belief.

"There is a certain degree of cohesion between alarms and metrics, as alarms are defined on metrics. However, I think we've achieved a good balance between cohesion and loose coupling in the Monasca architecture. I sometimes describe Monasca as a micro-services message bus based architecture."

OK, that's good.

"Referring to the architecture diagram at, https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Monasca#Architecture, the various components in Monasca are outlined. The API, Persister, Threshold Engine and Notification are independent components that reside in separate repos and are largely decoupled. They can be deployed together or independently. For example, there is no dependency between the Notification Engine and Persister, and you don't need to deploy the Notification Engine or Threshold Engine with Monasca if you are interested in only storing and retrieving time-series data. Or you could choose to go the other direction and only deploy the Threshold Engine, without the Persister and Notification Engine, or several other combinations. To address your concern, "Monasca seems to be taking a similar path in having a single service that does both." where both is alarms and metrics. I don't really see it that way, as Monasca is really a distinct set of components and services."

Interesting. That's certainly good to hear. To be blunt, I was bringing up this point as a test of whether the Monasca contributor community had communicated with the Ceilometer team to learn lessons from where that project has struggled. I still don't know whether that was the case...

"Would it be worthwhile to do an architectural and design walkthrough of Monasca to go into more detail?"

No, not at this time. Part of the big tent is not having architectural reviews be a graduation/inclusion requirement, and I'm not about to have one here. My point in bringing the API and the coupling points up is the following:

it indicates that the Monasca team has not been interested in working with the Ceilometer contributor community in improving the OpenStack Telemetry API nor collaborating with them to date.

The requirements for joining the Big Tent in OpenStack try to answer the question "are you 'one of us'?". I'm honestly on the fence about whether the Monasca contributor community really is interested in aligning with upstream OpenStack processes, including aligning with the upstream working groups (API working group included), upstream collaboration processes (IRC meetings, use of the mailing list for discussions, etc), and generally improving the OpenStack ecosystem for the good of the whole.

I just don't know yet. To me, it may be too early to tell. If we are going to ask the Fuel contributor team to demonstrate their alignment with upstream -- including working to get rid of forked/copied functionality from Puppet OpenStack, align with upstream CI systems, and have discussions about alignment of inventory management APIs with the Tuskar project, then I think it's hypocritical of the Technical Committee to let Monasca's submission pass without so much of a thought.

Best,

@JayPipes: Thanks for the feedback. I'll try to address the topic of Monasca involvement with Ceilometer and the overall OpenStack community first, and then follow-up to address your other comments.

Involvement with Monasca in the OpenStack community started at the Atlanta Summit where we did an architectural and design overview of Monasca to the Ceilometer team during the design summit. After the Atlanta Summit we had several meetings with Eoghan Glynn, the Ceilometer PTL at the time, and Eoghan attended the Monasca weekly meetings as a liaison to the Ceilometer team. Eoghan also attended the open review of the Monasca API which covered three sessions and was attended by four organizations. 

At the Paris Design Summit there was a joint session on collaboration opportunities between the two projects, see https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/kilo-ceilometer-monasca-collaboration. A couple of areas were identified. Monasca was also involved in other design summit sessions during the Paris Summit, such as https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/gnocchi-influxdb-opentsdb-mappin where members of the Monasca team have extensive expertise to share. Unfortunately, shortly after the Paris Summit, more direct interaction between the two projects subsided.

Several members of the Monasca team attended sessions on Ceilometer at the Vancouver Summit. Although we haven't become involved in the efforts yet, there were some areas that we were interested in becoming involved with. For example, the collection pipeline componetization work is very interesting to members of the Monasca team.

More recently, interactions between the Ceilometer and Monasca team have started up again. Members of the Ceilometer team attended a Monasca team meeting a few weeks ago. The minutes from that meeting are at, https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/Monasca_Weekly_Meeting_8-18-2015. We discussed potential areas to collaborate on including the alarm engine and data collection componetization work. I took an action item from that meeting to review Aodh and have completed that initial review and provided feedback. This is an area we could work together on and it would be mutually be beneficial to both projects.

Within HP, we have another team that has the responsibility of Ceilometer in addition to other areas of metering and billing. HP has always had developers in HP on the Ceilometer team and a commitment to Ceilometer. Some of them have been very active in the Ceilometer community. We also have members on the Monasca team from other organizations that are also active within Ceilometer too, and there is open dialogue between these representatives.

Several members of the Monasca team are also extremely active in other areas of OpenStack too. As mentioned above, Craig Bryant is involved in the infra team and current ranks 11th in reviews. As another example, there are members of the Monasca team that are very active in the OpenStack Operators community. There has also been involvement of the Monasca team in multiple Operators Mid-cycle Meetups and the Operators Monitoring Working Group sessions.

I want to emphasize that the Monasca team is in continual communication with the members of the Ceilometer team whether it is direct or indirect involvement. We are well aware of the learnings from the Ceilometer project and we've had an open dialogue with members of the Ceilometer team as well as representation on the Ceilometer team. There are multiple companies that remain strongly committed to Ceilometer and HP is one of them. We are investing significant resources in Ceilometer to improve the solution as well as leverage Ceilometer and not duplicate efforts and members of Monasca are involved in those efforts.

Another point that I want to address is that there has been feedback provided to the Ceilometer team by developers that are also involved with Monasca. For example, there has also been feedback on improving the Ceilometer API. 

Although I've mentioned HP several times, I want to mention that there is active participation from six major organizations right now, all of which engage in the OpenStack community, and that list is growing. I also think the timing is right to strengthen the relationship between the Monasca and Ceilometer teams and I would fully support that.

Regards --Roland"}, {'account_id': 16222, 'date': '2015-09-02 07:03:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2015-09-02 20:54:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi Jay, This reply will address the topic of API compatibility that you raised in your previous response.

The Monasca API addresses different use cases than what the Ceilometer API is focused on. At a 10000 foot view the two systems appear to  significantly overlap, but there are differences, and although in some cases they are subtle, they lead to supporting very different use cases.

Monasca is a general monitoring solution, whereas Ceilometer is directed at monitoring OpenStack resources. Currently, the Monasca team is focused on monitoring the physical and software infrastructure that is used to run OpenStack, as well as systems, services and applications that are not OpenStack resources. One of the focuses of Monasca has been on operational monitoring of the physical infrastructure and software services, such as RabbitMQ and MySQL, that are used to run OpenStack. In addition to supporting metrics, Monasca is designed to be a complete replacement for health/status reporting systems, such as Nagios/Icinga, and it is already doing so in production at scale today.

Monasca can also be used for application monitoring using it's built-in support for statsd. Via the RESTful API, which is the only method of supplying metrics in Monasca, support for true Monitoring-as-as-Service is enabled, in the style of web services monitoring companies such as Datadog, Librato and others. The Monasca Agent supports all these use cases.

Although the Monasca Agent supports monitoring VMs via the libvirt plugin, we see Ceilometer playing a synergistic role with Monasca in monitoring OpenStack resources. In fact, Monasca is leveraging Ceilometer as a data source via the multi-publisher pipeline capability in Ceilometer, to report samples for OpenStack resources. See, https://github.com/stackforge/monasca-ceilometer. We plan on also using the same mechanism for OpenStack notifications/events. Consequently, we are also very interested in supporting the data collection componetization work that Ceilometer is potentially pursuing. At some point the libvirt plugin in the Monasca Agent could be deprecated in favor of using Ceilometer for supplying metrics for all OpenStack resources to Monasca.

What this means is that Monasca consolidates operational monitoring, OpenStack resource monitoring, monitoring as a service and application monitoring to some extent, in a single API and service.

There are sometimes subtle and important differences between the APIs, such as resource registration and batching, that lead to significant usage, architectural and performance differences. This would require an additional discussion to cover the details on.

There are several more significant differences between Monasca and Ceilometer. Monasca includes a notification system that currently supports email, PagerDuty and webhooks. One of the more unique and complex areas of Monasca is that you don't create alarms, you create alarm definitions, which are templates that are used to automatically create metrics based on pattern matching in the Threshold Engine. This allows you to generalize alarm definitions over metrics and more easily support an elastic environment, where resources come and go.

Another area of differentiation is that Monasca is not just a data collection pipeline and service, but also addresses user-interface and visual analytics. A monitoring dashboard for Monasca has been developed for Horizon. Additionally, Monasca has been integrated as a data-source for the defacto standard for time-series visualization, Grafana.

Monasca is in the process of integrating support for complex event processing via the StackTach.v3 integration as well as support for Logging, in the style of Loggly, which is not in Ceilometer.

Regards --Roland"}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2015-09-08 18:39:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

two points:

(1 comment)

Roland, thanks for your answers, much appreciated.

I'm still a no vote on this one, however, at least at this point. I think it would be inconsistent of the TC to allow Monasca to "join the fun" when we've voted no to both Group Based Policy and to Fuel.

For Group Based Policy, we voted that down (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/161902) for a couple reasons. First and foremost, the GBP API seemed to replace the OpenStack Network API (that is, the RESTful API implemented by Neutron). I think I can make a pretty good case that the Monasca API indeed *replaces* a large part of the OpenStack Telemetry API. And, the fact that in this proposed patch, under "service: " in the projects.yaml file, you've put "telemetry" supports my position on this.

Secondly, for Group Based Policy, it was noted that true community collaboration seemed to be lacking. While I certainly see an improvement (and encourage it very much) in the community collaboration recently with the Monasca team, I note that it's only pretty recently improved (and yes, I acknowledge that the Monasca community has presented some things at the last few OpenStack conferences, but presenting some slides at a conference does not equate to true community collaboration and buy-in, as I'm sure you would agree). So, I think the jury is still out on this for Monasca. Great improvement, but if we've given the Fuel project a 2-3 month "prove yourself" period (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/199232/) to align with the Puppet OpenStack community and upstream processes, I think it would be inconsistent of the TC to not ask the same of the Monasca team. Nothing personal, I just want things to be consistent.

Finally, another condition we asked the Fuel project to meet was alignment of the continuous integration systems used in Fuel development with those of the upstream infra CI. Does the Monasca community have a plan/roadmap for aligning with the upstream CI systems, particularly for the remaining Java parts of the Monasca project? We asked Fuel to put this plan together. To not ask Monasca to do the same seems inconsistent to me.

Best,

-jay'}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2015-09-08 20:01:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

This proposal was reviewed during the TC meeting on September 08th, 2015. The TC agreed that it'd be better for both, the Monasca team and OpenStack, to give this proposal some extra time to mature. Here's a more detailed list of feedback that members of the TC provided during the meeting:

1. Integration tests are a not running as a gate job

Although there are unit test jobs, there are not yet integration test jobs exercising Monasca along with other OpenStack services. We place a high priority on integration tests, and given Monasca's maturity claims we think the lack of integration test gate jobs needs to be addressed. Ideally, these tests should be integrated with OpenStack's CI tools and use devstack to bootstrap services.

2. Host Monasca's source in gerrit

The goal of our "Open Development" requirement from [0] is to have all of the source for a project available in one canonical place to enable community contributors, downstream packagers, and other interested parties to access it the same way. The integration tests currently on github should be imported into gerrit, if they are suitable for use as a gate job. If not, then a new set of tests would be needed and we should discuss that further. If there are other components associated with Monasca or required for using Monasca and maintained by the Monasca core team, those should be available in gerrit, too.

3. Better integration with the rest of the community.

Monasca has begun holding meetings on IRC, but we would like to see more of a pattern of those meetings being successful given the history of using other, more exclusive, tools.

I'd also recommend folks in the Monasca team to take a look at the new project team guide[1]. This guide contains lots of material that is meant to help new projects joining the big tent to integrate better with the tools and workflows in the community. For example, it would be ideal and recommended to have a cross-project liaison that would help Monasca tracking cross-project matters.

[0] http://governance.openstack.org/reference/new-projects-requirements.html
[1] http://docs.openstack.org/project-team-guide/

(thanks to Doug for helping out w/ this summary)'}, {'account_id': 16222, 'date': '2015-09-11 07:17:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2015-09-11 14:34:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

[{'created': '2015-08-14 14:58:10.000000000', 'message': "Adding Monasca to OpenStack

Monasca provides a multi-tenant, highly scalable, performant, fault-tolerant
monitoring-as-a-service solution for metrics.  Metrics can be published to the
Monasca API, stored and queried.  Alarms can be created and notifications, such
as email, can be sent when alarms transition state.  Support for complex event
processing and logging is in progress.  Monasca builds an extensible platform
for advanced monitoring services that can be used by both operators and tenants
to gain operational insight and visibilty, ensuring availabilty and stability.

Currently, Monasca is hosted in Stackforge, but will move to OpenStack.  All
code has been developed under an Apache 2.0 license and has no restrictions on
distribution or deployment.  All Monasca code is submitted and reviewed through
OpenStack Gerrit [1].  The Monasca project maintains a core team that approves
all changes.  Bugs are filed, reviewed  and tracked in Launchpad [10].

Monasca integrates in with several OpenStack projects and services.  The Monasca
API uses Keystone for authentication and multi-tenancy.  Oslo libraries are used
by all components where applicable.  Keystone middleware is used by the Monasca
API.  The Monasca project is in the process of integrating with Ceilometer by
using the Ceilometer data collection pipeline as well as the Ceilometer API via
a Ceilometer to Monasca storage driver, which will enable Monasca to consume
OpenStack notifications from other OpenStack services [5].  A monitoring panel
has been developer for Horizon.  An integration with Heat for auto-scaling
support is under active development.

Monasca has been running weekly meetings from the start of the project.
Meetings are held on Tuesday's at 9:00 AM MST and are open to anyone that wants
to attend.  Currently, the Monasca PTL is Roland Hochmuth.  Regular elections
will be held to elect new PTLs and core members.

Monasca was initially discussed at the Atlanta Summit.  The first Monasca
mid-cycle meetup was held in August 2014 at which three companies attended.  At
the Paris Summit a session on Monsca was held.  In addition, at the Paris
Summit, there as a design summit session held to discuss areas for collaboration
between Ceilometer and Monasca.  A Monasca Liberty mid-cycle meetup was held on
August 7-8, 2015, and included six companies [9].  Monasca is planning on
holding Monasca specific sessions at the Tokyo Summit as well as joint sessions
with other OpenStack projects.  Monasca is interested in developing integrations
with Ceilometer, Heat, Mistral, Congress and others.  There have been several
local meetups on Monasca in 2015, including Austin, TX, Boulder, CO, and San
Francisco, CA.

Monasca has an extensive set of documentation.  Overall documentation and links
to documentation are at the Monasca Wiki [2].  The Monasca API is documented

"}, {'created': '2015-09-08 22:36:32.000000000', 'message': "Adding Monasca to OpenStack

Monasca provides a multi-tenant, highly scalable, performant, fault-tolerant
monitoring-as-a-service solution for metrics.  Metrics can be published to the
Monasca API, stored and queried.  Alarms can be created and notifications, such
as email, can be sent when alarms transition state.  Support for complex event
processing and logging is in progress.  Monasca builds an extensible platform
for advanced monitoring services that can be used by both operators and tenants
to gain operational insight and visibilty, ensuring availabilty and stability.

Currently, Monasca is hosted in Stackforge, but will move to OpenStack.  All
code has been developed under an Apache 2.0 license and has no restrictions on
distribution or deployment.  All Monasca code is submitted and reviewed through
OpenStack Gerrit [1].  The Monasca project maintains a core team that approves
all changes.  Bugs are filed, reviewed  and tracked in Launchpad [10].

Monasca integrates in with several OpenStack projects and services.  The Monasca
API uses Keystone for authentication and multi-tenancy.  Oslo libraries are used
by all components where applicable.  Keystone middleware is used by the Monasca
API.  The Monasca project is in the process of integrating with Ceilometer by
using the Ceilometer data collection pipeline as well as the Ceilometer API via
a Ceilometer to Monasca storage driver, which will enable Monasca to consume
OpenStack notifications from other OpenStack services [5].  A monitoring panel
has been developer for Horizon.  An integration with Heat for auto-scaling
support is under active development.

Monasca has been running weekly meetings from the start of the project.
Meetings are held on Tuesday's at 9:00 AM MST and are open to anyone that wants
to attend.  Currently, the Monasca PTL is Roland Hochmuth.  Regular elections
will be held to elect new PTLs and core members.

Monasca was initially discussed at the Atlanta Summit.  The first Monasca
mid-cycle meetup was held in August 2014 at which three companies attended.  At
the Paris Summit a session on Monsca was held.  In addition, at the Paris
Summit, there as a design summit session held to discuss areas for collaboration
between Ceilometer and Monasca.  A Monasca Liberty mid-cycle meetup was held on
August 7-8, 2015, and included six companies [9].  Monasca is planning on
holding Monasca specific sessions at the Tokyo Summit as well as joint sessions
with other OpenStack projects.  Monasca is interested in developing integrations
with Ceilometer, Heat, Mistral, Congress and others.  There have been several
local meetups on Monasca in 2015, including Austin, TX, Boulder, CO, and San
Francisco, CA.

Monasca has an extensive set of documentation.  Overall documentation and links
to documentation are at the Monasca Wiki [2].  The Monasca API is documented
[3].  The optional Monasca Agent is documented [4].

Monasca has several official deployment solutions available.  Ansible roles are
available [6].  Puppet modules  are available via the openstack organization
[7].  Monasca also has a turn-key development environment based on Vagrant,
Devstack and Ansible [8].

Monasca is continually deployed to test and production environments off of
master branch and maintains a very high level of quality.  The first major
release of Monasca was tagged for Kilo.  The second major release of Monasca
will be tagged for Liberty.

[1]: https://review.openstack.org/#/q/status:open+monasca,n,z
[2]: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Monasca
[3]: https://github.com/stackforge/monasca-api/blob/master/docs/
     monasca-api-spec.md
[4]: https://github.com/stackforge/monasca-agent
[5]: https://github.com/stackforge/monasca-ceilometer
[6]: https://github.com/search?utf8=%E2%9C%93&q=ansible-monasca
[7]: https://github.com/openstack/puppet-monasca
[8]: https://github.com/stackforge/monasca-vagrant
[9]: https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/monasca_liberty_mid_cycle
[10]: https://bugs.launchpad.net/monasca

Change-Id: I04eeb7651167ca2712f525af3f5b2b5d45dacb5f

commit_message:
Adding Monasca to OpenStack

Monasca provides a multi-tenant, highly scalable, performant, fault-tolerant
monitoring-as-a-service solution for metrics.  Metrics can be published to the
Monasca API, stored and queried.  Alarms can be created and notifications, such
as email, can be sent when alarms transition state.  Support for complex event
processing and logging is in progress.  Monasca builds an extensible platform
for advanced monitoring services that can be used by both operators and tenants
to gain operational insight and visibilty, ensuring availabilty and stability.

All code has been developed under an Apache 2.0 license and has no restrictions
on distribution or deployment.  All Monasca code is submitted and reviewed
through OpenStack Gerrit [1].  The Monasca project maintains a core team that
approves all changes.  Bugs are filed, reviewed  and tracked in Launchpad [10].

Monasca integrates in with several OpenStack projects and services.  The Monasca
API uses Keystone for authentication and multi-tenancy.  Oslo libraries are used
by all components where applicable.  Keystone middleware is used by the Monasca
API.  The Monasca project is in the process of integrating with Ceilometer by
using the Ceilometer data collection pipeline as well as the Ceilometer API via
a Ceilometer to Monasca storage driver, which will enable Monasca to consume
OpenStack notifications from other OpenStack services [5].  A monitoring panel
has been developer for Horizon.  An integration with Heat for auto-scaling
support is under active development.

Monasca has been running weekly meetings from the start of the project.
Meetings are held on Tuesday's at 9:00 AM MST and are open to anyone that wants
to attend.  Currently, the Monasca PTL is Roland Hochmuth.  Regular elections
will be held to elect new PTLs and core members.

Monasca was initially discussed at the Atlanta Summit.  The first Monasca
mid-cycle meetup was held in August 2014 at which three companies attended.  At
the Paris Summit a session on Monsca was held.  In addition, at the Paris
Summit, there as a design summit session held to discuss areas for collaboration
between Ceilometer and Monasca.  A Monasca Liberty mid-cycle meetup was held on
August 7-8, 2015, and included six companies [9].  Monasca is planning on
holding Monasca specific sessions at the Tokyo Summit as well as joint sessions
with other OpenStack projects.  Monasca is interested in developing integrations
with Ceilometer, Heat, Mistral, Congress and others.  There have been several
local meetups on Monasca in 2015, including Austin, TX, Boulder, CO, and San
Francisco, CA.

Monasca has an extensive set of documentation.  Overall documentation and links
to documentation are at the Monasca Wiki [2].  The Monasca API is documented
[3].  The optional Monasca Agent is documented [4].

Monasca has several official deployment solutions available.  Ansible roles are
available [6].  Puppet modules  are available via the openstack organization
[7].  Monasca also has a turn-key development environment based on Vagrant,
Devstack and Ansible [8]. Monasca integrates with DevStack via a Monasca
plugin [11] for DevStack. Tempest tests for Monasca [12] are also available.

Monasca is continually deployed to test and production environments off of
master branch and maintains a very high level of quality.  The first major
release of Monasca was tagged for Kilo.  The second major release of Monasca
will be tagged for Liberty.

[1]: https://review.openstack.org/#/q/status:open+monasca,n,z
[2]: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Monasca
[3]: http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/monasca-api/tree/docs/
     monasca-api-spec.md
[4]: https://git.openstack.org/openstack/monasca-agent
[5]: https://git.openstack.org/openstack/monasca-ceilometer
[6]: https://github.com/search?utf8=%E2%9C%93&q=ansible-monasca
[7]: https://git.openstack.org/openstack/puppet-monasca
[8]: https://git.openstack.org/openstack/monasca-vagrant
[9]: https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/monasca_liberty_mid_cycle
[10]: https://bugs.launchpad.net/monasca
[11]: https://git.openstack.org/openstack/monasca-api/devstack
[12]: https://git.openstack.org/openstack/monasca-api/monasca_tempest_tests

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-15 09:01:11.000000000', 'message': 'Add senlin project to big tent

This is a request to add Senlin [1] to the Big Tent.

Senlin is designed to be a generic clustering service for OpenStack clouds
that makes the creation and management of homogeneous objects as groups an
easier task. Examples of objects include Heat stacks, Nova servers, etc.
Senlin provides an open framework that consists of:

 - an engine that manages clusters and nodes and the primitives to operate
   them as abstract objects;
 - profile plugins that enable senlin to talk to a specific OpenStack
   service for object CRUD operations.
 - policy plugins that capture rule sets which are checked/enforced when
   object operations are performed, e.g. placement, deletion, scaling, health
   and others.
 - trigger plugins that customize the external signals/alarms/events that can
   trigger operations on clusters/objects/profiles/policies;

The project was started in Nov, 2014 after the Paris summit as a standalone
service that will offload the auto-scaling service from Heat. The scope was
then expanded to include other policies for a comprehensive clustering or
collection service on OpenStack. The project was openly discussed with the Heat
team during Vancouver summit. Plan is being developed for migrating the
existing auto-scaling support in a way that reduce (or totally avoid) user land
changes.

Senlin is also working with other OpenStack projects to explore collaboration
opportunities. For example, team has worked with intern students to manage
container clusters under the Magnum context. The goal is to investigate how to
manage the VM groups and container clusters so that these two layers can be
scaled, load-balanced in accordance with each other. A demo is scheduled on
the Tokyo summit.

Senlin strictly follows the "4 opens" principle of the community.
The project is fully licensed under the Apache 2.0 license. All code changes
are submitted and reviewed using the OpenStack infrastructure and gated
through gerrit[2][3][4]. Team has been using the +2/+A process for patch
reviews. The current unit test coverage is 90% and functional gate is in place
helping ensure everything works together. The project strictly obeys the
coordinated project interfaces, including tox, pbr, global-requirements etc.
All dependencies of the project falls within the range of global requirements.
The gating now runs pep8, py27, py34, docs tasks and optionally a functional
test.

The PTL was chosen by election to be Qiming Teng during Mitaka cycle. The PTL
serves as liason between the Senlin community and other projects to coordinate
the interactions with for example python-openstacksdk, heat, ceilometer, etc.
Team plans to excercise a PTL rotation among core contributors.

Project team has been using openstack-dev mailing list and freenode IRC
channel #senlin heavily for cooperation. The #senlin channel is logged [5] and
the logging is notified in the channel. Project team has weekly IRC meeting on
channel #openstack-meeting on 1300 UTC every Tuesday [6] to accommodate
contributors from east Asia and America.

Senlin has a well-documented, reasonably stable API [7] ready to be merged by
upstream project. It has documents for beginner users [8] and new developers
[9]. Developer team has been answering questions related to installation and/or
usage in IRC actively.

It is true that Senlin has been initiated by a single company but the project
has now attracted contributors from more than 6 affiliations. We have reasons
to believe the adoption by Big Tent will help encourage more contributions to

This is a request to add Senlin [1] to the Big Tent.

Senlin is designed to be a generic clustering service for OpenStack clouds
that makes the creation and management of homogeneous objects as groups an
easier task. Examples of objects include Heat stacks, Nova servers, etc.
Senlin provides an open framework that consists of:

 - an engine that manages clusters and nodes and the primitives to operate
   them as abstract objects;
 - profile plugins that enable senlin to talk to a specific OpenStack
   service for object CRUD operations.
 - policy plugins that capture rule sets which are checked/enforced when
   object operations are performed, e.g. placement, deletion, scaling, health
   and others.
 - trigger plugins that customize the external signals/alarms/events that can
   trigger operations on clusters/objects/profiles/policies;

The project was started in Nov, 2014 after the Paris summit as a standalone
service that will offload the auto-scaling service from Heat. The scope was
then expanded to include other policies for a comprehensive clustering or
collection service on OpenStack. The project was openly discussed with the Heat
team during Vancouver summit. Plan is being developed for migrating the
existing auto-scaling support in a way that reduce (or totally avoid) user land
changes.

Senlin is also working with other OpenStack projects to explore collaboration
opportunities. For example, team has worked with intern students to manage
container clusters under the Magnum context. The goal is to investigate how to
manage the VM groups and container clusters so that these two layers can be
scaled, load-balanced in accordance with each other. A demo is scheduled on
the Tokyo summit.

Senlin strictly follows the "4 opens" principle of the community.
The project is fully licensed under the Apache 2.0 license. All code changes
are submitted and reviewed using the OpenStack infrastructure and gated
through gerrit[2][3][4]. Team has been using the +2/+A process for patch
reviews. The current unit test coverage is 90% and functional gate is in place
helping ensure everything works together. The project strictly obeys the
coordinated project interfaces, including tox, pbr, global-requirements etc.
All dependencies of the project falls within the range of global requirements.
The gating now runs pep8, py27, py34, docs tasks and optionally a functional
test.

The PTL was chosen by election to be Qiming Teng during Mitaka cycle. The PTL
serves as liason between the Senlin community and other projects to coordinate
the interactions with for example python-openstacksdk, heat, ceilometer, etc.
Team plans to excercise a PTL rotation among core contributors.

Project team has been using openstack-dev mailing list and freenode IRC
channel #senlin heavily for cooperation. The #senlin channel is logged [5] and
the logging is notified in the channel. Project team has weekly IRC meeting on
channel #openstack-meeting on 1300 UTC every Tuesday [6] to accommodate
contributors from east Asia and America.

Senlin has a well-documented, reasonably stable API [7] ready to be merged by
upstream project. It has documents for beginner users [8] and new developers
[9]. Developer team has been answering questions related to installation and/or
usage in IRC actively.

It is true that Senlin has been initiated by a single company but the project
has now attracted contributors from more than 6 affiliations. We have reasons
to believe the adoption by Big Tent will help encourage more contributions to
its design and implementation, thus improve the diversity status of the team.

commit_message:
Add senlin project to big tent

This is a request to add Senlin [1] to the Big Tent.

Senlin is designed to be a generic clustering service for OpenStack clouds
that makes the creation and management of homogeneous objects as groups an
easier task. Examples of objects include Heat stacks, Nova servers, etc.
Senlin provides an open framework that consists of:

 - an engine that manages clusters and nodes and the primitives to operate
   them as abstract objects;
 - profile plugins that enable senlin to talk to a specific OpenStack
   service for object CRUD operations.
 - policy plugins that capture rule sets which are checked/enforced when
   object operations are performed, e.g. placement, deletion, scaling, health
   and others.
 - trigger plugins that customize the external signals/alarms/events that can
   trigger operations on clusters/objects/profiles/policies;

The project was started in Nov, 2014 after the Paris summit as a standalone
service that will offload the auto-scaling service from Heat. The scope was
then expanded to include other policies for a comprehensive clustering or
collection service on OpenStack. The project was openly discussed with the Heat
team during Vancouver summit. Plan is being developed for migrating the
existing auto-scaling support in a way that reduce (or totally avoid) user land
changes.

Senlin is also working with other OpenStack projects to explore collaboration
opportunities. For example, team has worked with intern students to manage
container clusters under the Magnum context. The goal is to investigate how to
manage the VM groups and container clusters so that these two layers can be
scaled, load-balanced in accordance with each other. A demo is scheduled on
the Tokyo summit.

Senlin strictly follows the "4 opens" principle of the community.
The project is fully licensed under the Apache 2.0 license. All code changes
are submitted and reviewed using the OpenStack infrastructure and gated
through gerrit[2][3][4]. Team has been using the +2/+A process for patch
reviews. The current unit test coverage is 90% and functional gate is in place
helping ensure everything works together. The project strictly obeys the
coordinated project interfaces, including tox, pbr, global-requirements etc.
All dependencies of the project falls within the range of global requirements.
The gating now runs pep8, py27, py34, docs tasks and optionally a functional
test.

The PTL was chosen by election to be Qiming Teng during Mitaka cycle. The PTL
serves as liason between the Senlin community and other projects to coordinate
the interactions with for example python-openstacksdk, heat, ceilometer, etc.
Team plans to excercise a PTL rotation among core contributors.

Project team has been using openstack-dev mailing list and freenode IRC
channel #senlin heavily for cooperation. The #senlin channel is logged [5] and
the logging is notified in the channel. Project team has weekly IRC meeting on
channel #openstack-meeting on 1300 UTC every Tuesday [6] to accommodate
contributors from east Asia and America.

Senlin has a well-documented, reasonably stable API [7] ready to be merged by
upstream project. It has documents for beginner users [8] and new developers
[9]. Developer team has been answering questions related to installation and/or
usage in IRC actively.

It is true that Senlin has been initiated by a single company but the project
has now attracted contributors from more than 6 affiliations. We have reasons
to believe the adoption by Big Tent will help encourage more contributions to
its design and implementation, thus improve the diversity status of the team.

[1]https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Senlin
[2]https://review.openstack.org/#/q/project:openstack/senlin,n,z
[3]https://review.openstack.org/#/q/project:openstack/python-senlinclient,n,z
[4]https://review.openstack.org/#/q/project:openstack/senlin-dashboard,n,z
[5]http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/irclogs/%23senlin/
[6]https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Meetings/SenlinAgenda

[8]http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/senlin/tree/doc/source/getting_started
[9]http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/senlin/tree/doc/source/developer

commit_message:
Pull server list cache setting via API

To ensure that we get numbers and not strings from OCC for cache
settings, we need to use the actual API for that, not direct data
introspection.

Change-Id: I457c624ebfcda6578417fb977ea3742a63507344

There are 2 things I don't quite like in this change:

1. You delete test_node_create_get_delete and add it back in next change, so this means that if these 2 changes are not merged simultaneously this will not be tested for some amount of time.

2. In the next change you move all the code added to another file, while it can be done here.

Add simple table structure Ironic CLI tests

Basic smoke tests for the Ironic CLI commands to check table structure
which do not require creating or modifying ironic objects.

commit_message:
Use o.vo fingerprint generation

Nova has fingerprint generation that is used to generate hashes of
versioned objects based on fields and remotable methods. This has been
moved to a fixture in o.vo, so now we can use that fixture to generate
the expected and actual fingerprints. We can then assert on these
values.

Change-Id: I64320e2cebae3e06e9cd8f2a1edca2fc2d42ec57

commit_message:
Deploy Docker compute role with tripleo.sh

The '--use-containers' flag will be specified to deploy the overcloud
in containers.  It needs to be added in addition to '--overcloud-deploy'.

Depends-on: Ic539b82b92e3fdd834750e591d8622b7dc85fc6d
Change-Id: I9302d401ae05316d6bb756286fef69c3a7a97420

commit_message:
Change the Atomic image name so it's less specific

The atomic image name in glance was being set to 'fedora-atomic'.
The glance image can be any form of atomic distro so we shouldn't
name this specifically 'fedora-atomic', but instead 'atomic-image'.

Change-Id: Ic539b82b92e3fdd834750e591d8622b7dc85fc6d

commit_message:

Other projects have updated to 1.8 or later for the minimum
tox version (nova, neutron), so we should probably do the
same.

Just to clarify, would Telemetry be the team name under which Ceilometer continues to be a project, or would =Telemetry be a name that users need to learn if they want to consume that functionality? Trying to get my arms around it from a marketing perspective to make sure we're not confusing folks..."}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2015-11-09 17:56:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

It would be the team name, Ceilometer being one of its project. (We also have Gnocchi and Aodh, and probably more coming)'}, {'account_id': 11360, 'date': '2015-11-09 19:01:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

So from an operator standpoint, we would continue to promote the individual project names (Ceilometer, Gnocchi, etc.), or would operators need to be familiar with the concept of the team and overall telemetry capabilities?'}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2015-11-09 19:48:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

No, I think we're good promoting the projects. The team is just an OpenStack governance concept."}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2015-11-09 20:08:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1 Rollcall-Vote+1'}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2015-11-09 20:24:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

the idea is that we want to stop overloading the Ceilometer term.

  - Ceilometer is a data collection service
  - Aodh is an alarming service
  - Gnocchi is a resource indexing and metric storage service

each of them provide a select set of Telemetry related functionality.'}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2015-11-10 02:11:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I would like more teams to think this way, that they provide a service or set of services. But I find this confusing as an outlier, an exception rather than the rule. I wonder if others will get the same feeling? Do we name teams and projects or collections of deliverables?'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2015-11-10 03:04:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1 Rollcall-Vote+1'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-11-10 10:27:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I don't think operators really need to learn about the concept of teams. And as far as the project navigator goes, we expose specific services there, not project teams.

As an example, we talked about Neutron and Kuryr (the projects) at the recent summit, we did not make the distinction that Kuryr was actually produced by the Neutron project team..."}, {'account_id': 1, 'date': '2015-11-10 17:49:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Rollcall-Vote+1 Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 2592, 'date': '2015-11-10 19:28:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1 Rollcall-Vote+1'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2015-11-10 19:29:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Rollcall-Vote+1'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2015-11-10 20:13:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1 Rollcall-Vote+1

commit_message:
Rename Ceilometer projects to Telemetry

The Ceilometer team and project took a lot of new deliverable recently under
its umbrella, such as Gnocchi and Aodh, and the Ceilometer term does not
identify the team and project correctly anymore.

During discussion at the Mitaka summit, it appeared that emphasizing the name
Telemetry as the name of the group of people and deliverable they produce is
way more accurate than just "Ceilometer", which is now only a deliverable
getting smaller and smaller.

Change-Id: I99d6c2416b8d395935daec945cfd4ae686ce76e9

Proposal itself is great however I have some question to implementation part and scope of changes. The most important question I have is how this change will be implemented/supported in other ceilometer services.

Having API running and healthy doesn't mean that ceilometer itself is working since other services may be broken. It would be ok to check only one service if ceilometer would run in single service process (all-in-one). This is not our case however.

I think that we should extend this spec and cover implementation of health checks for all ceilometer services not only API."}, {'account_id': 7052, 'date': '2014-06-12 21:01:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Adding support for health check in Ceilometer API

The health check allows Load Balancer (LB) and other
mechanisms to verify the availability of a service and
hence allow High Availability directing traffic to
different instances. The new API is v2/health and
supports HEAD verb for service only availability check
and GET verb for service and backend availability check.

blueprint ceilometer-api-health-check

Change-Id: Ib5ddef1b712aa16c52cdf2e1d980b4d1f01b1547

commit_message:
Limit type:service to user-facing services

Refine type:service definition so that it only applies to
classic OpenStack user-facing services, and not to internal
long-running agents.

Apply the new definition to current projects.

commit_message:
Use assertIs(Not)None instead of assert(Not)Equal

Instead of using assert(Not)Equal(None, ***), developers should
use assertIs(Not)None(***) to have more clear messages in case of failure.

Change-Id: I20dd008badde8a3e87a367e7ab791ace4e117fb7

Just to follow up here:
I renamed this from live-upgrade to partial-upgrade, taking Eoghan's comments to heart on the plane. What we (nova) can do today is really better described as a "partial upgrade" I think, where we can break the task of restarting things into pieces. I would distinguish "live" as a thing we can do once we can hit half the conductors, then the other half, and same with API such that requests can still be processed during the upgrade. Nova is close to getting to that, but I do think it's a different thing from just being able to logically break up the process to avoid atomic whole-service downtime while everything is completed.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-03 15:37:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

commit_message:
Introduce assert:supports-rolling-upgrade tag

The assert:supports-rolling-upgrade tag defines a standard minimum for
what we consider to be "rolling upgrade" capabilities in OpenStack
services. Project teams may assert that they follow at least
this policy.

This is an essential bit of information to communicate to our users,
and a key factor in assessing a given project's maturity.

Change-Id: I7ba9cdbe1b6ba026da374dd66e30611133538e91

Just to follow up here:

I renamed this from live-upgrade to partial-upgrade, taking Eoghan's comments to heart on the plane. What we (nova) can do today is really better described as a "partial upgrade" I think, where we can break the task of restarting things into pieces. I would distinguish "live" as a thing we can do once we can hit half the conductors, then the other half, and same with API such that requests can still be processed during the upgrade. Nova is close to getting to that, but I do think it's a different thing from just being able to logically break up the process to avoid atomic whole-service downtime while everything is completed.'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2015-11-03 15:34:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Introduce assert:supports-upgrade tag

The assert:supports-upgrade tag defines a standard minimum for
upgrade capabilities in OpenStack services. Project teams may
assert that they follow at least this policy.

This is an essential bit of information to communicate to our users,
and a key factor in assessing a given project maturity.

Change-Id: Iad564e22cd008a46f22a55204ee6780ef9c9b9dd
