@Thomas would be OK to move the binary data on a different repo and install them let's say only if sys.platform == 'win32' ?"}, {'account_id': 6476, 'date': '2015-11-02 20:26:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

As long as that one repo doesn't get into the big tent, and it is only used for a non-free platform such as Windows, that IMO ok."}, {'account_id': 11151, 'date': '2015-11-02 20:56:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: -Code-Review

@Thomas, ok, we propose the following steps:

1) Short term: We can move the binaries to a dedicated repo called openstack/freezer-bin. This repo will not be part of the big tent.

2) Mid term: The binaries will be re implemented in python, so there will be no need of that binaries anymore. We need some time to do this as we need to extend tarfile module to support incrementals compatible with tar meta data incremental files. We are also implementing a pure python rsync like implementation for block based incremental as per https://review.openstack.org/#/c/159804/

To be clear:
All the binaries we are using are generated using open source software (i.e. tar, find etc).

Please let us know if anything can be improved.'}, {'account_id': 6476, 'date': '2015-11-02 22:07:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Yes, the short term plan seems the correct thing to do.

But if I were you, I wouldn't go for the mid-therm plan. Re-implementing everything in Python, including super-complex stuff like tar and such, seems crazy to me. Why don't you just integrate yourself into free software projects like Cygwin? You could then just declare a dependency on the things you need..."}, {'account_id': 5202, 'date': '2015-11-03 16:30:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1

I would like to see Freezer included to Big Tent as the team is clearly willing to take the guidance and do things "OpenStack Way". I think any design decisions (what the project will implement or consume) should be done openly within the project listening community feedback rather than used for bikeshedding here.

I do not see any blockers against the Big Tent definitions.

Thomas:
I don't think it's fair to claim that project which wants to support non-free platforms with foss tools would be any less Open Source minded than project that wants to limit their openness to certain platforms only. Knowing that you haven't had any problems stripping vendored components from your packages, perhaps you can provide some guidance to the Freezer team how to make that part easy rather than attack against their will to support various platforms. Most of all as there is no closed source dependencies even in their windows support parts, I don't think that should be reason to exclude them from big tent. Thus I think inclusion and guidance is way better route than exclusion and driving them to "wrong" direction.'}, {'account_id': 14123, 'date': '2015-11-03 17:36:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1

I agree with Erno. 
All products used in freezer are released with a free software license and the user is able to download the code as per the free software license requirements even on closed source operating systems. Freezer team is not changing any program external to freezer so no obligation to release the changed code.'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-11-03 17:55:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1 Rollcall-Vote-1

Binary files have all been removed from the repo.

I'm not a huge fan of some of the code in the repo -- I think there is a lot of redundant code with things like oslo, I don't like the fact that the client program is called freezerc instead of freezer as all other OpenStack clients are named, and I don't really see where the API service comes into play -- but those aren't a reason not to welcome a team that seems to be following the OpenStack Way.

Thanks for the removal of the binaries. As others said, in OpenStack we produce source code, not binary distributions.

Your LICENSE.rst also differs significantly from the classic OpenStack LICENSE file. I suspect the cryptsoft mention was linked to the inclusion of OpenSSL binaries in bin/ and could be removed now ? If not could you explain why it's needed ? If you agree you should also strip it from all license headers in the source.

Also consider renaming LICENSE.rst to LICENSE and including the complete text of the Apache 2.0 license there. Otherwise it is missing from the source code."}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-11-09 10:38:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

freezer-web-ui also has no LICENSE file.

Overall I'm wondering if it's not a little too early for this one. IRC meetings were started two months ago, and there is little presence on the ML..."}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2015-11-09 16:44:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11: Code-Review-1

As Thierry, I also noticed the little presence on the mailing list and the fact that IRC meetings started just recently. I was ready to put that aside but there's also the problem related to the license files.

I'd like to mention, though, that I'm happy to see how the project has been structured to fit into openstack. The ui repo is a plugin for the dashboard, the api repo contains the service, whereas the freezer repo contains code that is also reusable from other parts.

The team has been active for a bit but it may need some extra time to integrate better with the overall community.

I'd be also interested in knowing what the deprecation guarantees of this project are?

http://governance.openstack.org/reference/tags/assert_follows-standard-deprecation.html"}, {'account_id': 11151, 'date': '2015-11-09 17:19:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

@Thierry:

Action items:
The following changes implements your recommendation:

- https://review.openstack.org/#/c/243158/
- https://review.openstack.org/#/c/243167/
- https://review.openstack.org/#/c/243185/

Here some additional info:
- We are terminating the usage of hipchat. That's why there's not big movement on IRC.

- There are strong reasons for us to expecting resources to be clearly split between more than one company in the near future :)

Why we think we are ready:

- It was very hard to manage to convince the company where we work to allocate resources and create a Team for the Freezer Project. This finally happened :)

- There were cases of external contributors that had no issues at all to be involved in the project.

- We believed from day 0 on this project and we invested enormous amount of time and effort to arrive to the current point, having a working solution. Since the beginning we did this for OpenStack. The 100% of the code was release opensource, in the OpenStack project and this what is going to happen in the future. No doubt about it :)

- We are doing all the requested changes and improvement as requested by the TC and other cores. It is also true that we need to have feedback that can be translated in actionable items, otherwise it's hard to execute from our side.

- Now that we reached a reasonable number of feature, we can focus more on IRC, publish conversation and so on. Please do not make this feedback a blocker."}, {'account_id': 11151, 'date': '2015-11-09 17:33:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

@thierry:

- Also we are going to post very soon the current state of Freezer and what is expected to do in Mitaka.

@Flavio:
Thanks I didn't knew about that link. This is what we are doing:

- Our API are currently at V1. We do support API version for the future. We think of doing this also according the release branching. For the freezer-agent (the component that execute the backups) and freezer-scheduler (the component that talks to the api and execute the freezer-agent) we are already doing that and is displayed on the help. We currently do not provide warning and deprecation from logs, we need to do that.

I think we can be compliant the reference tag provided by you and for some aspect we already are.

There's something I'd like to say about the concerns on too much contribution from a single company:

- In the beginning, I think it's common that this happen, as it frequently can be the case that a single entity allocate resources to create a workable solution for one project. This is the case of Freezer too."}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2015-11-10 03:34:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Code-Review-1

[{'created': '2015-10-27 13:55:55.000000000', 'message': 'Freezer application to join the Big Tent

Mission and Vision:
To provide the world most advanced Open Source [0]
and OpenStack based Backup Restore and DR as a service platform.
Full version available here [1].

The temporary PTL is Fausto Marzi.
Starting from January a new PTL will be elected by using the standard
OpenStack mechanism.

The #openstack-freezer IRC channel on freenode is logged and the channel is
notified of such logging [2]. Our public meeting logs are stored [3].

Many design aspect has been defined at the Vancouver Summit [4].

The project uses public code reviews on the OpenStack infrastructure.
A part the first 2-3 months of the project creation,
Freezer has been using the +2/+A process requiring two unique core
reviewers to review a patch.

Our gating runs pep8, pylint and other unittest and integration tests.
In the last weeks a Devstack plugin was walso implemented [5].

Currently there is a dedicated Team working on Freezer from one
of the top 3 Company contributors in OpenStack. There are also
external contributors to the project [6].

As this is a new project the number of contributors is not huge,
but there is a strong interest everywhere and the feedback from
the community was always positive and encouraging.

Freezer uses IRC and sometimes Hangout for most of the communication.

We are doing all our best to make this project useful and successfull
for the whole OpenStack Community.

Mission and Vision:
To provide tools for managing backup/restore and disaster recovery.
Full version available here [1].

The temporary PTL is Fausto Marzi.
Starting from January a new PTL will be elected by using the standard
OpenStack mechanism.

The #openstack-freezer IRC channel on freenode is logged and the channel is
notified of such logging [2]. Our public meeting logs are stored [3].

Many design aspect has been defined at the Vancouver Summit [4].

The project uses public code reviews on the OpenStack infrastructure.
A part the first 2-3 months of the project creation,
Freezer has been using the +2/+A process requiring two unique core
reviewers to review a patch.

Our gating runs pep8, pylint and other unittest and integration tests.
In the last weeks a Devstack plugin was also implemented [5].

Currently there is a dedicated Team working on Freezer from one
of the top 3 Company contributors in OpenStack. There are also
external contributors to the project [6].

As this is a new project the number of contributors is not huge,
but there is a strong interest everywhere and the feedback from
the community was always positive and encouraging.

Freezer uses IRC and sometimes Hangout for most of the communication.

We are doing all our best to make this project useful and successfull
for the whole OpenStack Community.

Freezer Project repositories:

- https://github.com/openstack/freezer/
- https://github.com/openstack/freezer-api
- https://github.com/openstack/freezer-web-ui

commit_message:
Freezer application to join the Big Tent

Mission and Vision:
To provide tools for managing backup/restore and disaster recovery.
Full version available here [0].

The temporary PTL is Fausto Marzi.
Starting from April a new PTL will be elected by using the standard
OpenStack mechanism and timeline [1]

The #openstack-freezer IRC channel on freenode is logged and the channel is
notified of such logging [2]. Our public meeting logs are stored [3].

Many design aspect has been defined at the Vancouver Summit [4].

The project uses public code reviews on the OpenStack infrastructure.
A part the first 2-3 months of the project creation,
Freezer has been using the +2/+A process requiring two unique core
reviewers to review a patch.

Our gating runs pep8, pylint and other unittest and integration tests.
In the last weeks a Devstack plugin was also implemented [5].

Currently there is a dedicated Team working on Freezer from one
of the top 3 Company contributors in OpenStack. There are also
external contributors to the project [6].

As this is a new project the number of contributors is not huge,
but there is a strong interest everywhere and the feedback from
the community was always positive and encouraging.

Freezer uses IRC and OpenStack related ML for all the communications.

We are doing all our best to make this project useful and successfull
for the whole OpenStack Community.

Freezer Project repositories:

- https://github.com/openstack/freezer/
- https://github.com/openstack/freezer-api
- https://github.com/openstack/freezer-web-ui

[0] https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/freezer-manifesto
[1] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/PTL_Elections_April_2015
[2] http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/irclogs/%23openstack-freezer/
[3] https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/freezer_meetings
[4] https://www.openstack.org/summit/vancouver-2015/summit-videos/presentation/freezer-the-openstack-back-up-as-a-service-platform
[5] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/233683/
[6] http://stackalytics.com/?project_type=openstack-others&release=all&metric=commits&module=freezer

commit_message:
Add trusts support to Glance v1 API

This code enables trusts support for v1 API
in 'upload' method. It will prevent possible errors
if token expires during long image upload and
adds the ability to renew the token if it's
required.

Change-Id: I448db37184abdd50e58d26ef40ea6b2ece8f07d2

commit_message:
Add trusts support to common client

It is an implementation of trusts mechanism in
Glance common client that is used to send almost
all utility requests.

Trusts become an addition to current reauthenticate
implementation and they  are used only if the client
got NotAuthenticated response from a server. In that
case client will try to renew user token and sent the
request again.

Change-Id: Icd676b6f784a4d91b496e1c4a886702a14e61f68

Modified the code for kilo version.

commit_message:
Update JS that adds classes for modal form errors

The JS that processes json error messages for modal forms was not
searching for or adding the correct classes to the HTML for display
the errors. This patch updates the JS so that once processed the
HTML matches the HTML that is returned in the non-json response of
the form.

Change-Id: Ib5ef39d02194ec6c31d69f534831bb0d28e0884c
Closes-Bug: 1443428

'}, {'created': '2015-08-20 06:57:10.000000000', 'message': 'Update Settings tab in the dashboard

By default the Settings tab is under user icon
drop down menu. Once the Settings option is selected
from this drop down menu then only it will be 
visible under dashboard tabs.

To resolve the ambiguity the Settings option is
removed from user drop down menu and added to 
the dashboard tabs permanently.


Closes-Bug : #1331370

Change-Id: I99ffed5b6a3083fa5b067a09b95061e03ee0aa5f
'}]
commit_message:
Update Settings tab in the dashboard

By default the Settings tab is under user icon
drop down menu. Once the Settings option is selected
from this drop down menu then only it will be 
visible under dashboard tabs.

To resolve the ambiguity the Settings option is
removed from user drop down menu and added to 
the dashboard tabs permanently.


Closes-Bug : #1331370

Change-Id: I99ffed5b6a3083fa5b067a09b95061e03ee0aa5f

commit_message:
Skip long-running jobs for release note changes

No need to run these jobs on reno patches. As of now,
skip for the Neutron repo. Each project may choose a
different strategy.

Change-Id: I28d7a43418cd180b5d17341f074f6f37c932694e

commit_message:
Revert pinning of astara to stable/liberty

This was put in place before prior to releasing Astara Liberty. All
our projects now have a stable/liberty and this can be unpinned.

Change-Id: I45bccff119d84bb27a6fb589119165c7cbf54dc1

commit_message:
Adding Identity NGProjects Table

This patch adds the projects table to the Identity NGProjects panel.
To test it, set DISABLED to False in _3021_identity_ng_projects_panel.py
then go to url /identity/ngprojects.

Change-Id: I23cd8699d09ee4a93e8ce76d304032cbae3de7e9
Partially-Implements: blueprint angularize-identity-projects

Hi Doug! In the "upper-constraints.txt" file at stable/kilo branch: "python-keystoneclient===1.6.0", so it seems there's no need to update requirements. https://github.com/openstack/requirements/blob/stable/kilo/upper-constraints.txt#L231 Please correct me if I'm wrong.'}, {'account_id': 6482, 'date': '2015-11-07 03:31:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

even better would be if I could get someone else to look at https://review.openstack.org/#/c/212515/ and we could include that in 1.3.3 since it's the only one not merged: https://review.openstack.org/#/q/project:openstack/python-keystoneclient+branch:stable/kilo,n,z"}, {'account_id': 7331, 'date': '2015-11-09 11:39:56.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-09 11:49:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

commit_message:
Dropdowns should have a consistent design

While working on making various dropdowns in Horizon Bootstrap
compliant, it was noticed that there are two distinct types of
dropdowns currently being used in Horizon.  This creates some style
inconsitencies.  This consolidates the styles so that it will be
easier to make the component theme-ready.

Partially-Implements: blueprint horizon-theme-css-reorg

Change-Id: Ib2be3fef3af01fcf85163f24cabb835e23ca2aff

commit_message:
Skip functional tests when test account4 is unauthorized

Five functional tests rely on swift test account4 being
properly configured in keystone (the tests are already
skipped with tempauth). A regression in devstack appears
to have caused account4 to not be correctly set up which
causes those five tests to fail.

This is a tactical change to skip those tests when the auth
for account4 fails, pending devstack being fixed. Note:

- we do not just skip the tests unconditionally; on a test
  system with correctly setup keystone accounts the tests
  are still run.

- the tests only skip if the auth fails with keystone for
  account4.

Change-Id: Iffef6d54554d1eb71524589cb58a06f874a6afc6
Related-Bug: 1508860

commit_message:
Move LinuxBridge related features to bridge_lib

This change moves from linuxbridge agent[1] to bridge_lib[2] bridge only
related features and adds functional tests.

[1] neutron.plugins.ml2.drivers.linuxbridge.agent.linuxbridge_neutron_agent
[2] neutron.agent.linux.bridge_lib

Partial-Bug: #1514548
Change-Id: Ieccb8f77fc833467a166557e227023f5c2a50d1b

Change stack-update-preview from POST to PUT

The stack-update-preview API uses PUT, not POST.

(df) Minor edits to method descriptions, for consistency.

I wouldn't spend to much time worrying about transport since it is going away when we bring in ksa.

Maybe, we could be a little more careful about where we log config information and avoid the general filter?  I'm not sure.

My only other thing is I'd love to have a setting in clouds.yaml log_anonymizer defauled to True that I can set to False if I want to see the pw/tokens."}, {'account_id': 8257, 'date': '2015-08-14 14:52:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'd rather we solve the current problem with the current code than hold out for something that may or may not be there when we need it (meaning: we go for 1.0 and ksa isn't ready and integrated). I'd also rather we solve it in the current code because an auth library should just handle auth, and the comment that it would be removing Transport has me extra leery of it."}, {'account_id': 1112, 'date': '2015-10-14 19:59:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-08-13 23:30:35.000000000', 'message': 'Anonymize logs by default

Anonymize all log messages by default. Strip out username, password,
token, tenant/project values, and anything else sensitive.

Anything written to a stream or file is anonymized automatically.
Users would have to explicitly turn off anonymizing.

Bug: 1470246
Change-Id: Ib79430d6283fbfc8232edfabc165f3da0abd0e2d
'}]
commit_message:
Anonymize logs by default

Anonymize all log messages by default. Strip out username, password,
token, tenant/project values, and anything else sensitive.

Anything written to a stream or file is anonymized automatically.
Users would have to explicitly turn off anonymizing.

Bug: 1470246
Change-Id: Ib79430d6283fbfc8232edfabc165f3da0abd0e2d

In an environment where reclaim_instance_interval is set to

if required by using 'nova restore <instance_id>')

commit_message:
stack delete fails when instance is soft deleted

In an environment where reclaim_instance_interval is set to
non-zero in nova, an delete request will only soft delete an
instance.(status=SOFT_DELETED, so that the instance can be reclaimed
if required by using 'nova restore <instance_id>')

Now in the above environment, when an delete stack is requested by
user, stack will hang until reclaim_instance_inerval or timeout.
Hence status=SOFT_DELETED for an instance should be handled by heat, which
this patch proposes.

Closes-Bug: #1377290

Change-Id: I86ea788131f113e3deb7aebfccecd7f5e4957ae5

commit_message:
WIP: Support fine grained filtering for list

Many GET calls that return a list support various query parameters to
return subsets of data. Some of them use name formats we'd probably
rather avoid due to consistency (camel case) and some we will be able to
build up from other resources (such as when URLs are needed out of
flavors when limiting server lists).

Change-Id: I01b89f68db53c8134671f8f2a4e2e294d57ce5c5

commit_message:
Add example to do CRUD operations on servers

This script offers a little CLI interface to exercise some of the Server
related code around creating, listing, updating, and deleting. It's
meant to show an example of what can be done with the Server resource.

    python -m examples.server_builder --create
    python -m examples.server_builder --update
    python -m examples.server_builder --list
    python -m examples.server_builder --delete

Change-Id: If0910361d1904e4fbaf57b3fff96dc5b0f9d9c59

commit_message:
Add ability to add custom overcloud image

Due to a bug in cliff argument parsing, the --os-image option for
specifying a different overcloud image was not working. The fix
included avoiding the conflict along with adding the ability to add a
QCOW2 image into glance without requiring presence of the default initramfs
and kernel overcloud files. There was also a trivial addition of the
ability to set the image name in Glance, though it isn't required.

The primary use case for this is to be able to specify an atomic image
for use in the overcloud:

openstack overcloud image upload --os-image-file \
Fedora-Cloud-Atomic-22-20150521.x86_64.qcow2 --os-image-name \
fedora-atomic

As far as the old intended (but non-working) behavior of changing the
overcloud image name goes, one can still set the OS_IMAGE environment
variable to override the default 'overcloud-full.qcow2'.

Change-Id: I6854af5df864808415126465be77939a0f767ec0

commit_message:
Add ability to get refreshable tasks from cluster

Add method to get a tasks supporting change of configuration.
Such tasks contain field 'refresh_on' with list of configurations
needed by specific task.

Related to  blueprint openstack-config-change

Change-Id: Ieda8a5221471af83da03a087d0e99d88c119422b

commit_message:
Revert "Robustify locking in MessageHandlingServer"

This reverts commit d700c382791b6352bb80a0dc455589085881669f.

This commit is causing a timeout/lock wait condition when using the in 
memory rpc bus. It exposed in the Nova unit / functional tests which use
this extensively.

Change-Id: I9610a5533383955f926dbbb78ab679f45cd7bcdb
Closes-Bug: #1514876

messages:

(5 comments)

Not certain about the problem description.

Also a few minor nits'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-10-21 12:21:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I believe the reason that deleted flavors were needed was because we weren't rolling this info into instances.

I think that if we are removing show for deleted flavors, it should be fully removed, for all users, without the ability to list that content. Especially as it is going to be inconsistent based on when deletes happen on the back end for those rows."}, {'account_id': 5754, 'date': '2015-10-22 05:23:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

yea, at least for the moment, the instance still can reference to a deleted flavorhttps://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/doc/api_samples/servers/server-get-resp.json#L17 , if user want to know this flavor detail, he need a way to query those deleted thing. Otherwise we should put the flavor info into the instance.'}, {'account_id': 5754, 'date': '2015-10-22 05:32:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

But I think we should show the 'deleted' field to user, let the user know this flavor already deleted."}, {'account_id': 6062, 'date': '2015-10-22 12:29:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Guess let a user query a deleted stuff is a little bit weird

if we really think it's a tradeoff that we don't want store those info into an instance, how about add a '--force' or 'read_deleted' flag so that the deleted one can be get

And I agree that a 'deleted'=True or False can be returned"}, {'account_id': 6062, 'date': '2015-10-22 13:04:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(4 comments)'}, {'account_id': 6062, 'date': '2015-10-22 13:26:08.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-22 13:34:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-nova-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/23/232523/2/check/gate-nova-specs-docs/d712304//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 5m 15s
- gate-nova-specs-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/23/232523/2/check/gate-nova-specs-pep8/653de51/ : SUCCESS in 2m 02s
- gate-nova-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/23/232523/2/check/gate-nova-specs-python27/2423a8c/ : SUCCESS in 2m 30s'}, {'account_id': 12898, 'date': '2015-10-23 00:25:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

Thanks!

Looks good to me.'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-11-10 17:58:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-2

The current direction is to try and remove soft_delete of flavors from the database, now we no longer need to keep the flavor around after a server has booted. A big part of that will be slowly removing the idea of returning deleted flavors.

I think we should error with 404 on deleted flavors.

We certainly don't want to add "deleted": true/false into the flavor returned. Thats the opposite direction to what I think we have previously agreed/talked about.'}, {'account_id': 6062, 'date': '2015-11-10 18:33:15.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Fix redstack (devstack changes broke ceilometer)

A recent commit in devstack (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/219207 )
now validates that all post-processed conf files specified in local.conf
exist.

We need to conditionally add the ceilometer.conf to this file, since it
may or may not be present.

Enabling Ceilometer was also broken, as it's now a member of the 'big
tent' so this was fixed as well

Two additional options were added to enable ceilometer notifications in
Nova and Cinder.  These can be activated by setting the following on
the command line or in options.rc (or ~/.redstack.options.rc).

CEILOMETER_NOVA_CONF=True
CEILOMETER_CINDER_CONF=True

Change-Id: I4181d751a1c35b581c7d56e157324d04c4ddec6b
Closes-Bug: #1513515

commit_message:
Added support to v2

Zaqarclient v2 currently has missing features that involve the
management of subscriptions, but in order to these to work it is
necessary to add other features such as 'queues', 'messages',
'claims', 'pools' and 'flavors'. I added 'queues' and 'messages' as a
priorital step before start working with the other features and with
subscriptions as well.

Change-Id: Iea082cbf9e1d0e4a745bc10e41e1206af6132fad

to a cell.

commit_message:
Revert "Add missing 'noop' checks to fuel-* projects"

The change being reverted caused fuel to share the change queue
with all noop projects.  Noop jobs may only used on projects that
have no other jobs.  If fuel needs to merge changes to stable
branches, it will need to create at least one job to run on those
branches.

This reverts commit 94430790d2845e26136e648caa836378cc21242c.

commit_message:
add "unreleased" release notes page

We need a release notes page to show notes for unreleased versions by
scanning the "current" branch. This ensures that notes files cannot be
merged if they break the releasenotes job.

Change-Id: I5d3fbf8e4ba724ee97d668250d129e80c7486e1b

commit_message:
Fix SNMP polling due to PySNMP version 4.3.0

Version 4.3.0 of PySNMP prettyPrint() method behaves differently
than previous versions, breaking all SNMP-polled metrics.

This locks the requirements down to < 4.3.0.

Change-Id: I9109249d7b34fd2698223d1cd9a34843a871d99d
Closes-Bug: #1504588

commit_message:
Set ZUUL_BRANCH using BRANCH if not available

In most cases, ZUUL_BRANCH is set in gate, but not all the time. One
exception is e.g. periodic stable jobs, where there is no actual patch
to validate, hence no ZUUL_REF or ZUUL_BRANCH is set. In that case, we
need to help zuul-cloner to determine the proper branch to fetch
neutron.

It could be achieved by e.g. hardcoding the branch using --zuul_branch
CLI argument passed into zuul-cloner. In this patch, I instead set
ZUUL_BRANCH to BRANCH that seems to be always present in all kinds of
jobs. It is then used by zuul-cloner to choose the correct branch.

This fixes the issue for stable/liberty periodic jobs for neutron-lbaas
when we tried to validate it against neutron/master.

Change-Id: I360239a1443f8d4e16210a1ef743912e1bf85f41

commit_message:
Add support of new vip formats based on net roles

The format of VIPs description in 7.0 was changed.
Special nailgun API serializer for compatiblity with current OSTF should removed in 8.0
It is required to fix VIPs format in OSTF

Closes-Bug: #1476174
Change-Id: I259ebb1e43db399283f2bf3715905172d9b6c170

commit_message:
Switch nova to leverage os_package_type fact

This change switches the logic that handles which type of debian or
ubuntu packages based on the operatingsystem fact to leverage the
os_package_type fact so that we can leverage Debian packages on an
Ubuntu based system

Change-Id: I6d62804699978289c7e2293dba6d24b5b8b1b002
Depends-On: I0a009c0a60062d40c558c1f8de95386ce253f930

commit_message:
Allow to set proxy parameters:
 * https/http/ftp for:
 - debootstrap
 - apt configs

Change-Id: Ia6a01fab402a112eddc3ec741f1707749d9c64c3
Implements: blueprint dynamically-build-bootstrap

This test illustrates that v2 tokens deleted by v3 do not work on v2.

commit_message:
Remove nova network support

nova-network was deprecated in Fuel 6.1 and was locked
as an option in Fuel UI. This patch removes deprecated
functionality.

Closes-bug: #1514212
Change-Id: Ic9e5628861d3b96bd6122de587fb223fdcc4f238

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-14 20:10:42.000000000', 'message': 'EC: support multiple ranges for GET requests

This commit lets clients receive multipart/byteranges responses (see
RFC 7232, Appendix A) for erasure-coded objects. Clients can already
do this for replicated objects, so this brings EC closer to feature
parity (ha!).

GetOrHeadHandler got a base class extracted from it that treats an
HTTP response as a sequence of byte-range responses. This way, it can
continue to yield whole fragments, not just N-byte pieces of the raw
HTTP response, since an N-byte piece of a multipart/byteranges
response is pretty much useless.

There are a couple of bonus fixes in here, too. For starters, download
resuming now works on multipart/byteranges responses. Before, it only
worked on 200 responses or 206 responses for a single byte
range. Also, BufferedHTTPResponse grew a readline() method.

Also, the MIME response for replicated objects got tightened up a
little. Before, it had some leading and trailing CRLFs which, while
allowed by RFC 7232, provide no benefit. Now, both replicated and EC
multipart/byteranges avoid extraneous bytes. This let me re-use the
Content-Length calculation in swob instead of having to hack around
it.

Change-Id: I16fc65e0ec4e356706d327bdb02a3741e36330a0
'}, {'created': '2015-06-01 19:02:34.000000000', 'message': 'EC: support multiple ranges for GET requests

continue to yield whole fragments, not just N-byte pieces of the raw
HTTP response, since an N-byte piece of a multipart/byteranges
response is pretty much useless.

There are a couple of bonus fixes in here, too. For starters, download

range. Also, BufferedHTTPResponse grew a readline() method.

Also, the MIME response for replicated objects got tightened up a

Change-Id: I16fc65e0ec4e356706d327bdb02a3741e36330a0
'}, {'created': '2015-06-02 20:45:21.000000000', 'message': 'EC: support multiple ranges for GET requests

This commit lets clients receive multipart/byteranges responses (see
RFC 7232, Appendix A) for erasure-coded objects. Clients can already
do this for replicated objects, so this brings EC closer to feature
parity (ha!).

GetOrHeadHandler got a base class extracted from it that treats an
HTTP response as a sequence of byte-range responses. This way, it can
continue to yield whole fragments, not just N-byte pieces of the raw
HTTP response, since an N-byte piece of a multipart/byteranges
response is pretty much useless.

There are a couple of bonus fixes in here, too. For starters, download
resuming now works on multipart/byteranges responses. Before, it only
worked on 200 responses or 206 responses for a single byte
range. Also, BufferedHTTPResponse grew a readline() method.

Also, the MIME response for replicated objects got tightened up a
little. Before, it had some leading and trailing CRLFs which, while
allowed by RFC 7232, provide no benefit. Now, both replicated and EC
multipart/byteranges avoid extraneous bytes. This let me re-use the

commit_message:
EC: support multiple ranges for GET requests

This commit lets clients receive multipart/byteranges responses (see
RFC 7233, Appendix A) for erasure-coded objects. Clients can already
do this for replicated objects, so this brings EC closer to feature
parity (ha!).

GetOrHeadHandler got a base class extracted from it that treats an
HTTP response as a sequence of byte-range responses. This way, it can
continue to yield whole fragments, not just N-byte pieces of the raw
HTTP response, since an N-byte piece of a multipart/byteranges
response is pretty much useless.

There are a couple of bonus fixes in here, too. For starters, download
resuming now works on multipart/byteranges responses. Before, it only
worked on 200 responses or 206 responses for a single byte
range. Also, BufferedHTTPResponse grew a readline() method.

Also, the MIME response for replicated objects got tightened up a
little. Before, it had some leading and trailing CRLFs which, while
allowed by RFC 7233, provide no benefit. Now, both replicated and EC
multipart/byteranges avoid extraneous bytes. This let me re-use the
Content-Length calculation in swob instead of having to either hack
around it or add extraneous whitespace to match.

Change-Id: I16fc65e0ec4e356706d327bdb02a3741e36330a0

[{'created': '2015-11-04 14:13:24.000000000', 'message': "Prepare $::os_package_type

We need this to be able to make decision of what style of package we are
working with: Debian style package (for example, it uses a
nova-consoleproxy package and not nova-novncproxy, or it has a
openstack-dashboard-apache, etc.), or just the Ubuntu style package.

This is needed, because in some cases, we are using the Debian style
packages but running under Ubuntu. For example, that's the case when
running with MOS over Ubuntu. For this case, a manual override is
provided, in the form of a /etc/facter/facts.d/os_package_type.txt
containing:
os_package_type=debian

In all other cases, we can consider that we're using vanilia (ie:
unmodified) distribution packages, and we can set $::os_package_type
depending on the value of $::operatingsystem.

Having the below snipets helps simplifying checks within individual
project manfiests, so that we can just reuse $::os_package_type
directly without having to also check if it contains a value, then
check for the content of $::operatingsystem (ie: what's below factors
the check once and for all).

Change-Id: I0a009c0a60062d40c558c1f8de95386ce253f930

commit_message:
Prepare $::os_package_type

We need this to be able to make decision of what style of package we are
working with: Debian style package (for example, it uses a
nova-consoleproxy package and not nova-novncproxy, or it has a
openstack-dashboard-apache, etc.), or just the Ubuntu style package.

This is needed, because in some cases, we are using the Debian style
packages but running under Ubuntu. For example, that's the case when
running with MOS over Ubuntu. For this case, a manual override is
provided, in the form of a /etc/facter/facts.d/os_package_type.txt
containing:
os_package_type=debian

In all other cases, we can consider that we're using vanilia (ie:
unmodified) distribution packages, and we can set $::os_package_type
depending on the value of $::operatingsystem.

Having the below snipets helps simplifying checks within individual
project manifests, so that we can just reuse $::os_package_type
directly without having to also check if it contains a value, then
check for the content of $::operatingsystem (ie: what's below factors
the check once and for all).

Change-Id: I0a009c0a60062d40c558c1f8de95386ce253f930

commit_message:
Add supported of patterns for groups in deployment_tasks.yaml

Orchestrator is able to run plugin on all groups by pattern:
*        - all groups
!<group> - exclude group
/<scope>/  - all groups in scope
!/<scope>/ - exclude all groups from scope

groups may be included in some scope
in this case group_name should have
a suffix (scope_name) after predefined delimiter

Change-Id: I55394a90e15afbd8688a0f608f411c32a156fcc0
Implements: blueprint deployment-tasks-patterns-for-groups
Closes-Bug: #1480930

commit_message:
Set node to ERROR status if IP doesn't match Admin networks

When a node group or cluster is deleted there can be some nodes in bootstrap
which have IPs corresponding to those deleted node groups. They cannot be provisioned
as dnsmasq configuration does not contain info about those networks anymore.
Such nodes should be marked so that user can understand they are not usable.
The best thing user can do in this situation is to reboot the nodes.

Co-Authored-By: Aleksei Kasatkin <akasatkin@mirantis.com>

Partial-Bug: #1495593

Change-Id: I402225fac73d254826479139cbf91ed03f037f95

commit_message:
Changed way to calculate allocation_pool:

* Retrieved default subnet & mask bits (IPv4 & IPv6) from tempest conf file
* Applied them for the subnet creation

* Modified get_ipaddress_from_tempest_conf name function for clarify the goal of the function

Change-Id: I9d1c8ec8d6cfa3459b788add5575db2cfa279531
Closes-Bug: #1514457

commit_message:
[Ironic] Add haproxy service for RadosGW on baremetal network

Enable RadosGW support in Ironic.
Added RadosGW haproxy service listen on baremetal VIP
Added noop tests

Change-Id: I2678b198e16a1f5c80c24f303794e89da16d1de0
Implements: blueprint fuel-integrate-ironic (partially)

commit_message:
Changed way to calculate allocation_pool:

* Retrieved default subnet and mask bits (IPv4 & IPv6) from tempest configuration file
* Merge them and apply for the subnet creation in test_create_port_in_allowed_allocation_pools function

* Modified get_ipaddress_from_tempest_conf name function to get_cidr_from_tempest_conf for clarify the goal of the function

Change-Id: I5597cfb62c432f01b8d85e48ead6805a5e3bb958
Closes-Bug: #1514457

commit_message:
Add unversioned client constructor

It's a very common pattern in OpenStack to have a base level client
file that has a client constructor that takes a version as the first
parameter. This allows developers to write code that just imports the
client, rather than relying on python import paths for version
selection, which in turn allows for future version autodetection with
things like microversions.

Closes-Bug: #1514732

commit_message:
Port type and options were not passed to ovn

OVN lswitch ports have type and options for specific ports such as
vtep. Port type and options were constucted but in function
_create_port_in_ovn() the parameters were not used, thus not passed
to OVN at all. This patch fixes it.

Closes-bug: #1514672
Change-Id: If4dae459dcb6540d19b51e303b44b677669dde53

commit_message:
Allows upload to fail early when missing formats

This checks that if a file argument is included in a
image create and disk and container format are missing
then it will throw an exception. Failing early will stop
the creation of images that fale to have there image data
uploaded, meaning the command will fail it a way that
would be more expected from operators.

Change-Id: Ie2f3e2c2f71835e6415036f5cfb22c20843b9f57
Closes-Bug: 1481341

commit_message:
Update cinder-manage man to match current options

Add missing 'volume update_host' and 'service remove' commands, and
remove 'storage management' and 'volume reattach' commands.

Change-Id: Ie37fb4288b1bea1035d934136454af186eb8b44c
Closes-Bug: #1512844

commit_message:
Add override_resources type

This resource type handle overriding already existing
config resources and creating not defined as well.

Co-authored-by: Dmitry Ilyin <dilyin@mirantis.com>
Co-authored-by: Bartosz Kupidura <bkupidura@mirantis.com>
Partially Implements: blueprint openstack-config-change
Change-Id: I4223c1fb1bfca48245068c6296149ff0370b8676

commit_message:
Revert "Robustify locking in MessageHandlingServer"

This reverts commit d700c382791b6352bb80a0dc455589085881669f.

This patches introduces dead-lock in code that does not rely on eventlet
nor its monkey-patching.

commit_message:
Adding docs/comments for glance config

Deployers who use a dollar sign ($) in their swift backend passwords for glance
will be unable to authenticate to the swift backend. This is due to how
oslo.config formats strings.  This patch adds documentation and comments to
the user_variables.yml to ensure deployers know how to escape those strings.

This patch also adds a commented variable for the auth version on swift
backends so that deployers are reminded to use the correct version number.

Closes-bug: 1514291

Change-Id: I717e9afb5af1160de67dc5d0f87985fde5ad393e

commit_message:
Robustify locking in MessageHandlingServer

This change formalises locking in MessageHandlingServer. It allows the
user to make calls in any order and it will ensure, with locking, that
these will be reordered appropriately. It also adds locking for
internal state when using the blocking executor, which closes a number
of races.

It fixes a regression introduced in change
gI3cfbe1bf02d451e379b1dcc23dacb0139c03be76. If multiple threads called
wait() simultaneously, only 1 of them would wait and the others would
return immediately, despite message handling not having completed.
With this change only 1 will call the underlying wait, but all will
wait on its completion.

We add a common logging mechanism when waiting too long. Specifically,
we now log a single message when waiting on any lock for longer than
30 seconds.

We remove DummyCondition as it no longer has any users.

Change-Id: I9d516b208446963dcd80b75e2d5a2cecb1187efa

commit_message:
Adding SOSReport on RHOS

SOSReport is a tool used by GSS and CWE to degug and validate RHOS
deployment. With SOSReport included we can start to preprocess
some task in the CI and enable the certifcation process.

Change-Id: Ib6fefd6eba01b9fc342ae176189c72d27c6fa7e2

commit_message:
add missing shortcut for HTTPProxyToWSGI middleware

we should've added a shortcut to oslo_middleware/__init__ to hide path.

additionally we shouldn't have added Middleware to class name as it's
redundant

Change-Id: Id581180c24006aa142eb8bf086eb7fc42835cff5
Closes-Bug: #1514507

I think these duplicate dependencies came in because we were not
correctly always installing "general" packages (see
Ie1b8d09369281059d21da61b2725a457f708ae9e)

Most of these are just extras for the lxml dependencies; I added zlib
devel to general for glance (seems pretty generic), and then that can

Change-Id: I44b14ca15c64fad9daf1ac8d851704b02ea2eae0
'}]
commit_message:
Clear out some duplicate package dependencies

I think these duplicate dependencies came in because we were not
correctly always installing "general" packages (see
Ie1b8d09369281059d21da61b2725a457f708ae9e)

Most of these are just extras for the lxml dependencies; I added zlib
devel to general for glance (seems pretty generic), and then that can
go too, as all other packages are specified.

Change-Id: I44b14ca15c64fad9daf1ac8d851704b02ea2eae0

commit_message:
Add reno for release-notes

Add renote to automatically generate release notes - the same way other
OpenStack projects do it.
For details see
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-November/078301.html

Change-Id: Iac8f34ae3490b7788c989b17be3e6a616e65c676

commit_message:
Handle NO_DOMAIN status

Previous to this patch, when MiniDNS got a `NO_DOMAIN` status back,
it didn't do anything to handle it. Domains just hung in ERROR.

closes-bug: #1416264
Depends-On: I08d1eed1874eccb51b6a614f5e69207dd74196eb
Change-Id: I4348f714868f38c2549c516fe83cce608c0c8d59

[Debian Install Guide] Upgrade for Chapter 4

Identity Service sections were rewritten:
- Install and configure (without Apache now)
- Create projects, users, and roles
- Verify operation

Implements: blueprint installguide-liberty-debian

[{'created': '2015-11-06 11:03:06.000000000', 'message': 'Add policy check when user operate to display project detail.

When user who have no "admin" role try to show project detail from project list display,
error occurs (authority error) . And redirect to login display .
So, modify to show link if login user have authority to get_user.
In case of not having it, display project name as just plain text.
Closes-Bug:#1513784

Change-Id: I41307b8730ebce4afcd9678847fb85465a667e52
'}]
commit_message:
Add policy check when user operate to display project detail.

When user who have no "admin" role try to show project detail from project list display,
error occurs (authority error) . And redirect to login display .
So, modify to show link if login user have authority to get_user.
In case of not having it, display project name as just plain text.
Closes-Bug:#1513784

Change-Id: I41307b8730ebce4afcd9678847fb85465a667e52

commit_message:
[Reports] Colorize Pie chart errors in red

This patch makes Pie chart `errors' values always colored red.

NOTE:
  This is done by rewriting of Pie chart colorizing,
  because currently used version 1.1.15-beta of NVD3 has a bug
  which does not allow to colorize only selected values
  and keep other values colorized automatically.

  Recent version 1.8.1 of NVD3 has this bug fixed, however
  it has another unpleasant bug with stuck tooltip, so version
  upgrade has not been used.

  Possible colors are the same as generated by D3 - hardcoded set
  of 19 colors id actually an output of
  d3.scale.category20().range() (the largest D3 colors set),
  excluding red color (#d62728) which is reserved for errors.

Change-Id: I4ea9ba6ce3b01b107496171e2cf304252b862ca3

commit_message:
Import images publicly when package is public

When importing a package using package import wizard on the dashboard,
required glance images are imported before having chosen the
visibility of the package (is-public). With this commit, when the
package is set "public" in the final step of the wizard, the glance
images are also set "public".

Closes-Bug: #1507139
DependsOn: I9460360e84cc40d7414aa5cd9f7367f5a80b8466

Change-Id: I64e0572f4986919593b4cf40dac178fcbee9bf6f

commit_message:
Fix Database Migrations Documentation

Database Migrations Documentation shows the usage of
bin/barbican-db-manage.py which no longer exists. This
patch updates the documentation to showing how to run
the command rather than the file.

commit_message:
Update error status on a NO_DOMAIN error

When mdns returns a NO_DOMAIN on a create or
update zone, then mark the zone as in error. The
periodic recovery will later retry.

Change-Id: I5b4545af03869cddf5c4702d8235b057c9c784de
Closes-Bug: 1442221

commit_message:
Port dashboard router tests on Python 3

* Decode HTTP body from UTF-8 to get text on Python 3
* tox.ini: add routers tests to Python 3

Partial-Implements: blueprint porting-python3
Change-Id: Idc93818c4b62f782035604090b7c6fda459cf6fa

I think you need to update your commit message to be about just the auth_interface. 

So there's currently no dependency from keystoneclient -> keystoneauth and i'm not sure how i feel about adding that. It might be inevitable but i was hoping to just make a clean break and have that moved over. At least you will need to add it to requirements.txt

If we do this the way to do it would be in keystoneclient/auth/base.py do AUTH_INTERFACE = keystoneauth1.plugin.AUTH_INTERFACE because it would need to work for everything using the old value. particular change covers the non-federated
project listings also.

commit_message:
Retrieve AUTH_INTERFACE object from keystoneauth

This patch changes the AUTH_INTERFACE object to
keystoneauth1.plugin.AUTH_INTERFACE so that it passes the
check at keystoneauth1.identity.base.get_endpoint.

Co-Authored-By: Doug Fish <drfish@us.ibm.com>

Change-Id: Iaf48707ef82c1d4b873e07644580dd9572ce0992
Partial-Bug: #1471943

commit_message:
VMware: Relocate volume only during no disk space

During volume extend, we try to relocate the volume to a
different datastore if there is an error during vCenter
extend API call. But we need to relocate the volume to a
different datastore only if there is no space in the
current datastore to accommodate the extended volume. This
patch fixes the issue by relocating the volume only if the
exception raised is NoDiskSpaceException. It also refactors
the code to remove a redundant helper method for extending
virtual disk.

Closes-Bug: #1506422
Change-Id: Ic64eb697b49ffb3a435ffc4d969b5b7f79af91c6

commit_message:
Baremetal network in Fuel UI

When Ironic enabled in environment, baremetal network and
baremetal parameters appear on Networks tab.

This commit also removes some artifacts from the old hacks
in the network tab code.

Related to blueprint support-baremetal-network-in-ui

Change-Id: I322939174d938d3f6e8e95cb0ac53ddbcb02abd4

commit_message:
Test for pacemaker resources when disk is full

 Adding test case for covering filling root situation on
 primary controller.
 Move _action_health_check to ostf_base_actions.py.
 Add _action_health_check_all to ostf_base_actions.py.

 Partial-Bug: #1500446

Change-Id: I8e08867de41519f786f106e62dbfa1cd8380516a

commit_message:
Let os-client-config handle session creation

More things than shade need consistent Session creation, so we moved
a copy of the shade code into os-client-config to allow python-*client
to consume the same logic. Now that it's there, consume it in shade and
remove the need for shade to know/duplicate the logic.

Depends-On: Ide4c613cc143a0b8a3f36130989b57e808b2530f
Change-Id: I86cdb3cdd2710ef302520184ccfcb1605384f706

commit_message:
Add new stack area chart and update home

This commit includes a new chart type, stack area chart. It also updates
the dashboard home to use it instead of the old chart line for job rates.

Change-Id: I67d27d71434650428f48726c87918eaa9861923b

commit_message:
Murano CI: add new jobs and refactored scripts

1. Split job scripts into logical blocks
2. Update job definitions
3. Replace identical jobs with job templates
4. Add coverage job

Co-Authored-By: Victor Ryzhenkin <vryzhenkin@mirantis.com>

Change-Id: I8555879f1c008fca72da1a42191b55718d56b942

commit_message:
Add mount automation example based on Zaqar

This example consists of three parts:
- Server side hook module
'contrib.share_driver_hooks.zaqar_notification' that can be enabled in Manila
- Client side consumer module
'contrib.share_driver_hooks.zaqar_notification_example_consumer' that can be
used in any user machine.
- Common module 'contrib.share_driver_hooks.zaqarclientwrapper' that is used
by server and client side modules for initialization of Zaqar client.

Details of its usage are described in file
'contrib/share_driver_hooks/README.rst'

Change-Id: I5e802ee2e2a4dd36db92865b0ba82e73c1fa86d4

commit_message:
Refactor & fix incorrect default args

Fix:
  1. Default arguments should not be mutable
  2. Set could be created without set() call (little faster)
  3. Redundant parenthesis (readability)
  4. lambdas is strictly not recommended by PEP8, especially as class variables
  5. fix old style classes (not inherited from object)
Update-reason: rebase

Closes-Bug: #1512671

Change-Id: Id8314b76848278b67da898600240b59cf76a7328

commit_message:
Install requirements for services on ambari image

This installs list of base requirements for services
on ambari images.

The list of packages is following:
 * rpcbind, unzip, curl, tar, snappy-devel - required for
   datanode-related packages
 * redhat-lsb, nc - as requirement of hadoop_2_3_2_0_2950 package
 * zip - required for oozie-related packages
 * fuse-libs - as requirement of hadoop_2_3_2_0_2950-hdfs-fuse
   package

Closes-bug: 1502886
Change-Id: I1732d0a1ee6a43da9556277a8ba7097bd4dc26db

commit_message:
Validate the input of properties of nodes.

Validate input of cpus, local_gb and memory_mb. They should be
non-negative integers. Keep the flexibility for admin to set them
equal to zero.
And bump Node object to 1.14.

Co-Authored-By: Josh Gachnang <josh@pcsforeducation.com>
Change-Id: Ifbd0a822253a2a5c228f43fe85b8c29ad49f42f7
Close-Bug: #1487331

commit_message:
Port project instance tests to Python 3

* Fix division: replace a/b with a//b to get integers
* test_clean_file_upload_form_invalid_data(): use a byte string, not
  an unicode string for the test. The test ensures that decoding from
  UTF-8 fails.
* quotas: replace filter() with a list-comprehesion to get a list on
  Python 3.
* tox.ini: add the following tests to Python 3.4

  - openstack_dashboard.dashboards.project.instances.tests
  - openstack_dashboard.test.tests.quotas

* tox.ini: add also
  --exclude-dir=openstack_dashboard/test/integration_tests to
  openstack_dashboard tests on Python 3.4

Partial-Implements: blueprint porting-python3
Change-Id: I7caed713222b50ffec431155e6f91b543f7df466

commit_message:
refine the sahara installation guide

From the Juno version, we have the OpenStack client to identify
the component.So wo can substitute OpenStack client for keystone
to identify the sahara.
I checked the OpenStackClient commands guide:
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/OpenStackClient/Commands#endpoint
The OpenStackClient API version is:API v2.0

The OpenStackClient command is:
os endpoint create
    --publicurl <public-url>
    [--adminurl <admin-url>]
    [--internalurl <internal-url>]
    [--region <endpoint-region>]
    <service>

amd the keystone command is:
keystone endpoint-create
    [--region <endpoint-region>]
    [--service_id <service-id>]
    [--publicurl <public-url>]
    [--adminurl <admin-url>]
    [--internalurl <internal-url>]

Change-Id: I5ac44f009275fc855647bbc626cdf7f7a7026c92

commit_message:
Take shared networks into account for quotas

Previously, shared networks were ignored by collecting used
networks; the "Create network" button is still enabled, but
network creation is forbidden by neutron due to quota reached.

Change-Id: I97360e354ccb7c2aa58012f737a7e9c67f8d3ad6
Closes-Bug: #1513795

commit_message:
Missing stuff for Kafka in Ambari plugin

Open ports for Kafka Broker (default 6667) and also
open port for ZooKeeper (default 2181).

Change-Id: Ifabdcfa295de03a2b1a120bf291c7b876948e921
Closes-bug: 1512661

commit_message:
Reduce duplicated code in test_linuxbridge_neutron_agent

This change defines and uses get_linuxbridge_manager method which
mocks some methods in order to instantiate and returns a
LinuxBridgeManager instance, this method allows to remove some
duplicated code from test_linuxbridge_neutron_agent.

Partial-Bug: #1514548
Change-Id: Ib54a01406938b4937af2af5fca7a71b5758d4482

commit_message:
Fixes bug: AttributeError when trying to use local_network_vswitch

The attribute named _local_network_vswitch was called as local_network_vswitch
in the agent resulting in an AttributeError.

This fix adds the propper naming, _local_network_vswitch.

Change-Id: If6ac53656b18d4698953e8357030d59723aad2dc
Closes-Bug: #1514313

Add breadcrumb to more details pages

This patch adds basic Breadcrumb nav to the detail pages for Data
Processing, Databases, Metadata Definitions and Routers.

commit_message:
Use ListOpt for default_aggregation_methods option

Use the latest ListOpt from oslo.config 2.5.0 for
default_aggregation_methods option so the generated sample config file
will contain the correct default value format.

Closes-Bug: #1506431
Change-Id: I12b701ae42f49dbde5d8a5b639cb1a70859713d4

commit_message:
Add python-kollaclient as a deliverable to kolla

python-kollaclient was voted to be accepted into the Kolla code
base by the core reviewer team as an open source contribution
from Oracle.  The repository contributors have all signed the
CLA and all code has been contributed under the ASL while
under CLA agreement.

The original repository which will be copied into the openstack
namespace via project-config is here:

git://oss.oracle.com/git/openstack-kollacli.git

Change-Id: I453b360d509bf99a9049f8ce406964abe37eff12

commit_message:
Controlled logging from nailgun

This commit adds functionality to control logging from nailgun
by APP_LOGLEVEL value in the '/etc/nailgun/settings.yaml'

Also it reduces log level of notices indicating hardware_info_locked
when trying to fetch metadata to debug because they are much
too frequent.

Change-Id: I9d2ff84df1d663be363d2f1f7dc7d5e141bfdf27
Closes-Bug: #1510151

commit_message:
Add ShellinaboxConsole to SSH driver

Currently there is no support to get the console in dev
and test environments, this blueprint implements console
driver ShellinaboxConsole to support console access for
SSH driver using 'virsh console'.

Change-Id: I5dac030bc22a00e06ff3ab79a17151dbe4f23104

commit_message:
loop all ebtables tables

ebtables has 3 built in tables, if we don't call them out we only get
'filter' (per man page).

Change-Id: I52360cbb3b910cb492b61e2314848cc29dcd8266

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-23 05:09:25.000000000', 'message': 'Fixup RPM db path when building Fedora on Ubuntu

On Debian/Ubuntu installs of RPM, /usr/lib/rpm/macros sets

  %_dbpath  %(echo $HOME/.rpmdb)

which makes quite a bit of sense, because RPM is not the system
packager and thus RPM is setup to install things into a hierarchy in
the users homedir.

However, this messes things up when building a Fedora chroot on an
Ubuntu platform.

We use RPM & yum from the base-system to bootstrap the Fedora chroot.
While both obey --root flags, they still pick up the %_dbpath macro
and so end up creating the RPM database in <chroot>/home/user/.rpmdb

After we have bootstrapped yum/dnf, we execute further installation
commands from inside the chroot -- where we now have the Fedora
version of /usr/lib/rpm/macros and hence have _dbpath set to
/var/lib/rpm -- except there is no rpm database there.

Should anyone be finding this in the future, the actual issue that
appears is

  $ sudo chroot /opt/dib_tmp/image.b6B5S3f6/mnt dnf makecache
   Error: Failed to synchronize cache for repo 'fedora' from \
    'https://mirrors.fedoraproject.org/metalink?repo=fedora-$releasever&arch=x86_64': \
    Cannot prepare internal mirrorlist: file "repomd.xml" was not found in metalink

Note the issue there is that $releasever is not expanded, because the
rpmdb where this info is kept is not populated.

The trick is to make sure we override this value when using the host
rpm/yum to setup the chroot.  The bare rpm calls, which we use to
install the repos, have a --dbpath argument where we can override
this.  yum does not however, so we override this in the global
~/.rpmmacros while we are installing the packaging tools and
dependencies into the chroot.

Copious comments are included, because this is super-confusing.

Change-Id: I20801150ea02d1c64f118eb969fb2aec473476f7

commit_message:
Fixup RPM db path when building Fedora on Ubuntu

On Debian/Ubuntu installs of RPM, /usr/lib/rpm/macros sets

  %_dbpath  %(echo $HOME/.rpmdb)

which makes quite a bit of sense, because RPM is not the system
packager and thus RPM is setup to install things into a hierarchy in
the users homedir.

However, this messes things up when building a Fedora chroot on an
Ubuntu platform.

We use RPM & yum from the base-system to bootstrap the Fedora chroot.
While both obey --root flags, they still pick up the %_dbpath macro
and so end up creating the RPM database in <chroot>/home/user/.rpmdb

After we have bootstrapped yum/dnf, we execute further installation
commands from inside the chroot -- where we now have the Fedora
version of /usr/lib/rpm/macros and hence have _dbpath set to
/var/lib/rpm -- except there is no rpm database there.

Should anyone be finding this in the future, the actual issue that
appears is

  $ sudo chroot /opt/dib_tmp/image.b6B5S3f6/mnt dnf makecache
   Error: Failed to synchronize cache for repo 'fedora' from \
    'https://mirrors.fedoraproject.org/metalink?repo=fedora-$releasever&arch=x86_64': \
    Cannot prepare internal mirrorlist: file "repomd.xml" was not found in metalink

Note the issue there is that $releasever is not expanded, because the
rpmdb where this info is kept is not populated.

The trick is to make sure we override this value when using the host
rpm/yum to setup the chroot.  The bare rpm calls, which we use to
install the repos, have a --dbpath argument where we can override
this.  yum does not however, so we override this in the global
~/.rpmmacros while we are installing the packaging tools and
dependencies into the chroot.

Copious comments are included, because this is super-confusing.

Change-Id: I20801150ea02d1c64f118eb969fb2aec473476f7

commit_message:
Don't use /etc/fuel/client.yaml

This patch removes usage of the old default
settings file. Users must use user-side configuration
file that is generated to $XDG_CONFIG_COME.

Related-Bug: #1458361
Change-Id: Ie2defd31c7ddc205fec3f0fcc864990098e37fb1

commit_message:
Tenant fetcher sometimes return wrong result

For now, the tenants getting method in tenant fetcher include the following
processing logic: modify (remove some items) the sequence (tenant list) being
iterated over in the loop, which may cause unpredictable result.

As described in python official documentation, if you need to modify the list
you are iterating over, you must iterate over a copy. This patch applied this
rule to tenants getting method.

https://docs.python.org/2/tutorial/controlflow.html
http://stackoverflow.com/questions/2896752/removing-item
-from-list-during-iteration-whats-wrong-with-this-idiom

Change-Id: I917484f0b1666da06636c811893f900923fd1e69
Closes-Bug: #1512560

I don't think this problem related only to our driver. Probably it exists in all RemoteFS children, which support snapshots.
The problem is in race between server stopping and deleting a snapshot.
Here is a script, which reproduces the problem sometimes:

#!/usr/bin/env python

import sys
import os
from cinderclient.v1 import client
from novaclient import client as novaclient
import time


def wait_for_vol_status(volid, status):
    while 1:
        vol = vc.volumes.get(volid)
        if vol.status == status:
            break
        print 'vol %s: %s' % (volid, vol.status)
        time.sleep(1)

def wait_for_snap_status(snapid, status):
    while 1:
        snap = vc.volume_snapshots.get(snapid)
        if snap.status == status:
            break
        print 'snap %s: %s' % (snapid, snap.status)
        time.sleep(1)

def wait_for_server_status(srvid, status):
    while 1:
        srv = nc.servers.get(srvid)
        if srv.status == status:
            break
        print 'srv %s: %s' % (srvid, srv.status)
        time.sleep(1)


USER = os.environ.get('OS_USERNAME')
PASS = os.environ.get('OS_PASSWORD')
TENANT = os.environ.get('OS_TENANT_NAME')
AUTH_URL = os.environ.get('OS_AUTH_URL')

vc = client.Client(USER, PASS, TENANT, AUTH_URL, service_type="volume")
nc = novaclient.Client("2", USER, PASS, TENANT, AUTH_URL)


vol1 = vc.volumes.create(imageRef='3927d7a9-1e2d-4c56-8ab1-315256af3f91', size=5)
wait_for_vol_status(vol1.id, 'available')

snap1 = vc.volume_snapshots.create(volume_id=vol1.id)
wait_for_snap_status(snap1.id, 'available')


flavors = nc.flavors.list()
for flavor in flavors:
    if flavor.name == 'm1.zzz2':
        break
else:
    raise Exception("Couldn't find flavor %s" % 'm1.zzz2')

srv = nc.servers.create('qwe', None, flavor,
                block_device_mapping_v2 = [{'source_type': 'volume',
                                           'destination_type': 'volume',
                                           'uuid': vol1.id,
                                           'boot_index': 0}])
wait_for_server_status(srv.id, 'ACTIVE')

srv.stop()
snap1.delete()'}, {'account_id': 12661, 'date': '2015-06-15 16:07:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
fix cleanup of test_volume_boot_pattern

A error occurs in my environment (vzstorage):

_volume_snapshot_delete /opt/stack/nova/nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py:1947
Error occurred during volume_snapshot_delete, s
Sending error status to Cinder.
 Traceback (most recent call last):
   File "/opt/stack/nova/nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py", line 2018, in volume_snapshot_delete
     snapshot_id, delete_info=delete_info)
   File "/opt/stack/nova/nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py", line 1950, in _volume_snapshot_delete
     rebase_bw, rebase_flags)
   File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/eventlet/tpool.py", line 183, in doit
     result = proxy_call(self._autowrap, f, *args, **kwargs)
   File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/eventlet/tpool.py", line 141, in proxy_call
     rv = execute(f, *args, **kwargs)
   File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/eventlet/tpool.py", line 122, in execute
     six.reraise(c, e, tb)
   File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/eventlet/tpool.py", line 80, in tworker
     rv = meth(*args, **kwargs)
   File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/libvirt.py", line 865, in blockRebase
     if ret == -1: raise libvirtError ('virDomainBlockRebase() failed', dom=self)
 libvirtError: Requested operation is not valid: domain is not running

This is a temporary fix for it. But further investigation is needed.

Change-Id: Ia66f3304bed198d40e4b8686ba2b6c5b9a17b6ca

commit_message:
Add floating ip table for neutronv2 datasource driver

This commit collects information of floating ips from
neutronv2 client and adds to floating_ips table of
neutronv2 datasource driver.

Change-Id: I0be65b45ccee38e6735956a2f058db67aea04847
Implements: blueprint neutronv2-floating-ip-table

commit_message:
Forbid launching services with 0 or negative number of workers

Added a safety check that validates that workers is a
positive number.
Added UTs.

Change-Id: I04f79ec56d0b77ca97c19de15502b48510802184

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-09 11:26:24.000000000', 'message': 'Add upper cap for Keystone module in Neutron tests

Currently tests from Neutron module takes the latest Keystone module which is
not fully compatible with the current state of tests.
Adding a cap to the latest Kilo tag of Keystone module (6.1.0) to avoid issues

Change-Id: I45b96c2642d309ea1cfa4a0625d888d9cb9b6231
'}]
commit_message:
Add upper cap for Keystone module in Neutron tests

Currently tests from Neutron module takes the latest Keystone module which is
not fully compatible with the current state of tests.
Adding a cap to the latest Kilo tag of Keystone module (6.1.0) to avoid issues

Change-Id: I45b96c2642d309ea1cfa4a0625d888d9cb9b6231

commit_message:
Use direct links to HDP distribution

It's preferable to use direct links to HDP
distribution in hdp local mirror element, because
depending on version of distribution links can be totally
different.

Change-Id: I5f82bd83d3bd6de462dce2d15920589e7bb0f0c6

commit_message:
Remove ServiceClient from policy_client

ServiceClient will be removed soon .
A client can directly be inherited from RestClient instead.

Change-Id: Icd855f3a94a16ea9ece7302641a8451377afdd8f
